dvl.name: Bayonetta
dvl.desc: A witch possessing magical powers, Bayonetta was discovered sealed away in a coffin at the bottom of a lake 20 years ago. With almost no memories of her previous life, the one thing she remembers is her mission to exterminate the Angels. Currently working with undertaker-cum-informant Enzo, she hates cockroaches and cry babies. The name "Bayonetta" was given to her by Rodin, owner of "The Gates of Hell".

dvl.name: Bayonetta☆
dvl.desc: A witch possessing magical powers, Bayonetta was discovered sealed away in a coffin at the bottom of a lake 20 years ago. With almost no memories of her previous life, the one thing she remembers is her mission to exterminate the Angels. Currently working with undertaker-cum-informant Enzo, she hates cockroaches and cry babies. The name "Bayonetta" was given to her by Rodin, owner of "The Gates of Hell".

dvl.name: Jeanne
dvl.desc: Like Bayonetta, Jeanne is also an Umbra Witch and a survivor of the witch hunts that occurred 500 years ago. With abilities and skills similar to Bayonetta, she is adept at performing Wicked Weaves and summoning the Infernal Demon Gomorrah, making her a worthy rival.

dvl.name: Jeanne☆
dvl.desc: Like Bayonetta, Jeanne is also an Umbra Witch and a survivor of the witch hunts that occurred 500 years ago. With abilities and skills similar to Bayonetta, she is adept at performing Wicked Weaves and summoning the Infernal Demon Gomorrah, making her a worthy rival.

dvl.name: Gabriel
dvl.desc: One of the four major archangels in the angel hierarchy. The angel who gave the Annunciation to the Blessed Virgin Mary, Gabriel's name comes from the Sumerian word for "governor". Though most angels are depicted as being androgynous, Gabriel is sometimes considered to be female, due to depictions of her with features resembling those of a young girl.

dvl.name: Raphael
dvl.desc:
One of the four major archangels in the angel hierarchy. His name means "healer".
He is said to be the guardian of the Tree of Life that stands at the center of the Garden of Eden.

dvl.name: Uriel
dvl.desc: One of the four major archangels in the angel hierarchy. His name means "Flame of God",  and he is in charge of all celestial phenomena. On Judgment Day, he will pass judgement on the sins of the living and the dead.

dvl.name: Masakado?
dvl.desc:
Taira no Masakado. A legendary samurai of the mid-heian period.
After conquering Kanto, he declared himself the new emperor of Japan, but soon fell to Hidesato Fujiwara and Sadamori Taira. He was enshrined to quell his spirit, and later became known as the guardian deity of Kanto.

dvl.name: Human Malice
dvl.desc:
Taira no Masakado. A legendary samurai of the mid-heian period.
After conquering Kanto, he declared himself the new emperor of Japan, but soon fell to Hidesato Fujiwara and Sadamori Taira. He was enshrined to quell his spirit, and later became known as the guardian deity of Kanto.

dvl.name: Vairocana
dvl.desc:
A king of the Asura in Hindu myth. Son of Prahlada and father of Bali. His name means "One Who Shines On All", and he is also known as Maha (Great) Vairocana. 
He was the enemy of Indra, the leader of the Devas, and was eventually vanquished by Indra.
In Buddhism he is known as Dainichi Nyorai, and is sometimes thought to be the universe itself.

dvl.name: Atavaka
dvl.desc: Among the eight Yashaou, he is the god of warfare and protection in Buddhist lore. Also called the Great General Myo-o. Originally a child-eating demon in Hindu mythology, he was incorporated into Buddhism and became a protector figure. It is said that when Siddhartha died, he imparted the teachings of Buddha to the gods and made them swear to protect humanity.

dvl.name: Hecate
dvl.desc: Her duty sees the dead and those who incur the wrath of gods suffer by her extremely cruel hands. She is master of the Furies, goddesses of revenge. Her name means "she who acts from afar," and is associated with the moon. Later, when she was turned into a demon, she began to be depicted as having three heads, a dog's, a lion's and a horse's.

dvl.name: Gozu-Tennoh
dvl.desc: A Japanese Shinto-Buddhist syncretism and guardian deity of Gion Shoja. He is also called Muto Tenjin. In ancient China, he was said to be the son of Xi Wangmu and had a castle in northern Tenjiku with 80,000 subordinate deities. In Onmyodo, he is considered to be the god Tendo-Jin. Though many theories about his true identity exist, the Gion Gozu-Tennoh Goengi claims he is Yakushi Nyorai (Buddha) of the Pure Land. Many worship him to ward off pestilence.

dvl.name: Tiamat
dvl.desc:
The primordial goddess of Babylonian lore whose form resembles a dragon. She governs the sea and gave birth to many deities with her consort Apsu, the god of fresh water. When war broke out between her and the gods, she spawned 11 monsters to fight by her side, but they were defeated by the leader of the gods, Marduk. Her body was first ripped apart and then used to create the world.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Moloch
dvl.desc:
An ancient Middle Eastern god worshipped in Canaan.
He is also known as "The Ruler of the Land of Tears," and "The Horrid King Besmeared with Children's Blood and Parents' Tears." A bronze statue of a man with a bull's head was placed at his altars.
In the Bible, he is known as a savage pagan god.

dvl.name: The 6th Angel
dvl.desc:
An entity strikingly similar to the Angel that attacked New Tokyo-Ⅲ. It is a fake created by Jabo Kakuryu in order to rattle Shinji Ikari's heart.
Though normally appearing as a kind of crystalline octahedron, it will change shape and attack based on the situation. The original 6th Angel fought with the Evas and was destroyed by a positron cannon.

dvl.name: The 10th Angel
dvl.desc:
An entity strikingly similar to the Angel that attacked New Tokyo-Ⅲ. It is a fake created by Jabo Kakuryu in order to rattle Shinji Ikari's heart.
It can deploy numerous A.T. Fields to create a solid defense, launch powerful attacks using rays of light, and can even consume its opponents and steal their abilities.
The original 10th Angel was a difficult foe, described as "the most powerful refusal type."

dvl.name: Lucifer
dvl.desc: The one who rules hell and all of its inhabitance, formerly known as the archangel of light. His name means "morning star" and before he fell, was the chief of the Seraphim. With a third of Gods angels on his side, Lucifer rebelled against God. He was defeated by Gods superior forces however, and in hell awaits his chance to strike again.

dvl.name: Morrighan
dvl.desc:
A goddess appearing in Celtic mythology. One of the three goddesses of war. Her name means "Great Queen." She is said to be a deification of sovereignty and control that presides over destruction and victory.
In Celtic mythology she professed her love to Cu Chulainn, but was rejected. In anger, Morrighan transformed into various animals to obstruct his battle, but to no avail. She would later appear as an old woman and have Cu Chulainn heal her wounds. Afterwards, she offered him her aid.

dvl.name: Metatron
dvl.desc: The greatest of all the angels. He is the angel of many names, "the voice of God" and "the angel of contracts" are but two of over 70. He is even suspected to be god himself. Most archangels have the suffix "el" that means "servant of god." Metatron does not have this and his name translates to "the one who serves behind the throne." In Judaism, Metatron was the one who guided Moses and parted the sea in his escape from the Egyptian army. For this Metatron is held in the highest regard.

dvl.name: Metatron
dvl.desc: The greatest of all the angels. He is the angel of many names, "the voice of God" and "the angel of contracts" are but two of over 70. He is even suspected to be god himself. Most archangels have the suffix "el" that means "servant of god." Metatron does not have this and his name translates to "the one who serves behind the throne." In Judaism, Metatron was the one who guided Moses and parted the sea in his escape from the Egyptian army. For this Metatron is held in the highest regard.

dvl.name: Loup-Garou
dvl.desc:
A type of werewolf originating in France. Though they appear human during the day, they take on their beastly form at night and attack humans.
Loup-Garou were once human, but were made into werewolves by a curse. It is said that there is no way to turn someone who has become one back to normal.

dvl.name: Artemis
dvl.desc:
A goddess of hunting and virginity appearing in Greek mythology, who is said to be a twin of the sun god Apollo.
She bears the title "Goddess Who Rains Down Arrows," and is also recognized as a bringer of pestilence and death.
Artemis fell in love with Orion, son of Poseidon, but Apollo, who was displeased by this, tricked Artemis into shooting Orion dead. It is said that, in order to comfort his daughter, Zeus raised Orion into the heavens and made him into a constellation.

dvl.name: Michael
dvl.desc: His name means "Who is Like God" and is one of the archangels. When Lucifer rebelled against God, the great strategist Michael was the one to defeat and trap Lucifer. He is well known for many other spectacular deeds, and to this day has a strong following in Europe.

dvl.name: Shiva
dvl.desc: The Hindu creator and destroyer of the world. Along with Vishnu, Shiva is one of the most revered gods in the Hindu faith. There is a belief that he will destroy the world near its end, purifying it during its reconstruction. He uses his destructive force towards demons, and bestows blessings on to those who worship him. His weapon is a trident of light, and his third eye is said to be able to set the world ablaze.

dvl.name: Anthrasax
dvl.desc: The dark God of Destruction that brought the world to the brink of ruin in only seven days. She is a wicked, grotesque god who seeks the annihilation of all humanity and civilization. She was sealed by the combined might of the four kingdoms, one of which was Meta-llicana. But because of an invasion by the Dark Rebel Army, it is feared she will rise again.

dvl.name: Shiisaa
dvl.desc:
An ancient holy beast from Okinawa, modeled after the lion.
The name Shisa comes from the Sanskrit word for lion "Simha".
This holy beast is said to protect houses from evil and grant great fortune.
There is a custom to place a ceramic figure of the Shisa on the roof of a house to ward off evil and bring good luck. Locals believe that the spirits of the dead turn into fireballs and are the cause of house fires which the Shisa are said to prevent.

dvl.name: Makami
dvl.desc: A wolf god of Japanese folklore. People originally feared the Makami, eventually that strong emotion deified the beast. The Makami can see into the heart of humans, protecting those who are good but punishing those who are evil. It is often drawn on prayer boards to prevent fires and thefts. At the same time, however, it was feared as a man-eater.

dvl.name: Chimera
dvl.desc: A beast that is part lion, part goat, and part snake.  In Greek mythology its father is the giant Typhon and mother the snake god Echinda. While in Lycia, the rampaging Chimera was slain by the mighty hero Bellerophon on his steed the Pegasus. To the Hittites, Chimera is a symbol representing the seasons, each animal part representing a different one. From its unique look any new animal species that is genetically crossbred is also called a Chimera.

dvl.name: Anubis
dvl.desc:
Egyptian god of the underworld.
In ancient Egyptian art work, Anubis is portrayed as having a human figure with dark skin and the head of a jackal. He weighs the hearts of the dead to determine their fate.
When Osiris was killed by Seth, Anubis was the one who reanimated the body, hence known for his skill in mummification.

dvl.name: Barong
dvl.desc: A greatly worshiped beast god that dwells in the forests of Bali. Adorned with mirror like jewels, every 210 days a festival is held for this lion like beast. Once an evil demon that was feared, through ritual became the guardian of the people. As a symbol of good, it is fated to war with Rangda, the avatar of evil, for all eternity.

dvl.name: Heqet
dvl.desc: The Egyptian goddess of water and fertility. She is usually depicted as a frog or woman with a frog's head and archaeological findings of frog statues are often thought to represent her. As the symbol of fertility, midwives in ancient Egypt were called the 'Servants of Heqet'.

dvl.name: Unicorn
dvl.desc: A mythical white horse from European lore, with a spiraled horn in the middle of its forehead. Its unique horn is said to have healing and other magical properties. The story goes that greatness will come to the one who can capture this fantastic beast. Though that is no easy task for the Unicorn only reveals itself to the purest of young maidens.

dvl.name: Apis
dvl.desc: The bull-god of Ptah, the god of creation in Egyptian lore, deeply worshiped in the Memphis region. Apis was conceived by the union of a cow and a ray of light from the heavens. It is said to have 29 distinct identifying marks, such as a diamond on its forehead and an eagle mark on its back.

dvl.name: Baihu
dvl.desc: One of the Ssu Ling, celestial creatures in Chinese lore. The Four beasts were divided equally throughout the land to protect the five emperors in ancient China. There is even a mural depiction of them in the Kitora Tomb in Japan. Baihu, the white tiger, is protector of the west and represents the season of autumn. In ancient times the tiger was considered the king of all beast and Baihu their leader.

dvl.name: Sleipnir
dvl.desc: Odin's eight-legged horse of Norse lore. Not only can it run at incredible speeds but it can also fly and ferry the dead to the heavens. Its father was Svadilfari and its mother was Loki in the guise of a female horse, given to Odin as a gift. It is also used as a symbol of the gallows. The tree from which Odin himself hug in the underworld to retrieve the Runes, was also called Sleipnir.

dvl.name: Sphinx
dvl.desc: A beast from Greek mythology with the head and breasts of a beautiful woman, the body of a lion and hawk-like wings. In a rage, the goddess Hera sent Sphinx to punish the people of Thebes, where Sphinx asked a riddle of those attempting to pass, eating those who could not answer. The hero Oedipus answered correctly and in shock threw herself off a cliff, to her death. However, in Egyptian lore she was worshiped as a symbol of the sun god.

dvl.name: Lailah
dvl.desc:
An angel in Judeo-Christian lore that presides over conception.
She is the intermediary between pregnant women and God. When a woman conceives a child, the seed is given to God, who then decides the child's sex, appearance, and destiny. After such things are decided, a new soul is placed into the woman's womb.

dvl.name: Sandalphon
dvl.desc: Angel of heavenly hymns. His name means "brother" and is the twin of Metatron. Sandalphon is a giant whose head reaches heaven and a man could spend a life time trying to climb him but never reach the top. He is also responsible for deciding the gender of a child in the womb and there are even theories of him actually being a woman.

dvl.name: Azrael
dvl.desc: The angel of death. Azrael holds a book in which all names are inscribed. A name is erased from record when one dies. He is hideous to behold with a body covered in hundreds of eyes and mouths. With his many eyes he watches and punishes those who sin.

dvl.name: Mastema
dvl.desc: An angel who serves by persecuting evil in Jewish folklore. As the commander of demons, he is permitted to test the faith and hearts of humans. Although in the fragments of Zadok and Dead Sea Scrolls, Mastema is mentioned as "the father of all evil" "the bringer of misfortune" or "the one who flatters God".

dvl.name: Michael
dvl.desc: His name means "Who is Like God" and is one of the archangels. When Lucifer rebelled against God, the great strategist Michael was the one to defeat and trap Lucifer. He is well known for many other spectacular deeds, and to this day has a strong following in Europe.

dvl.name: Metatron
dvl.desc: The greatest of all the angels. He is the angel of many names, "the voice of God" and "the angel of contracts" are but two of over 70. He is even suspected to be god himself. Most archangels have the suffix "el" that means "servant of god." Metatron does not have this and his name translates to "the one who serves behind the throne." In Judaism, Metatron was the one who guided Moses and parted the sea in his escape from the Egyptian army. For this Metatron is held in the highest regard.

dvl.name: Pele
dvl.desc: The Hawaiian volcano goddess. She is lava that became the deity of fire, lightning and dance. She is known for her beauty, passion and temper, spewing lava onto those who anger her turning them to stone. Pele is highly worshiped by the islanders for it is believed that she dwells in the sacred Mt. Kilauea.

dvl.name: Kushinada
dvl.desc: A deity from Japanese mythology that governs fertility and fields. Princess Kushinada was youngest of the eight daughters born to Ashinazuchi and Tenazuchi. All of her sisters were sacrificed to the giant snake Orochi but when it was her turn, she was saved by Susano-o and became his wife.

dvl.name: Isis
dvl.desc: The mother goddess of Egypt. She is wife and sister to Osiris, god of the underworld. When the God Seth dismembered and threw Osiris into the Nile River, it was Isis who brought him back to life. Soon after their son Horus was conceived. Originally the goddess of harvest, she is also known for being "the goddess of resurrection" or "the moon goddess." Not only was she worshiped in Egypt, but even Greece and Rome as well.

dvl.name: Kikuri-Hime
dvl.desc:
The goddess of Shirayama, also called Shirayama-Himie.
She mediated the well-known argument between Izanagi and Izanami in Yomi no kuni, the land of the dead. Soon after the two made up, and conceived Susano-o and Amaterasu. She is the goddess of love and marriage, also known as "Kukuri" which means to bring people together.

dvl.name: Skadi
dvl.desc:
A Nordic goddess of winter, and daughter of a giant. According to legend, all the gods will return to her at the end of Ragnarok for her name contains the meaning "shadow."
After her ill-fated marriage to Njord the god of the sea and wealth, she happily remarried Ullr the god winter.

dvl.name: Asherah
dvl.desc: A goddess from Ancient Semitic religion, married to the Lord of the Mountains Amurru. She is thought of as the Mother of all Gods. As the goddess of love and fertility she was worshiped in ancient Babylonia. She is also known as Astarte in other religions.

dvl.name: Angel
dvl.desc:
Ninth of the nine orders of angels.
They are closest in nature to humans. The word angel means "Emissary" in Hebrew and it is said that there are twice as many of them as there are humans. They watch over individuals and warn those who stray from the path.

dvl.name: Archangel
dvl.desc:
Eighth of the nine orders of angels. 
As their name indicates they were higher in the hierarchical order but over time fell through the ranks. Their duty is to minister to humans and deliver messages. They are also the warriors of Heaven and lead Heaven's forces during times of battle.

dvl.name: Principality
dvl.desc:
The seventh of the nine orders of angel.
As the advocates of heaven, their purpose is to guard cities and nations, and watch over the leaders of state. They also fight off demons when need be.

dvl.name: Power
dvl.desc:
The sixth of the nine orders of angels.
It is said that they were the first of the angels to be created. They are the first line of defense in the hallways of Heaven to prevent demons from entering. In ancient Greek they are called "Exia" which means "the ones who are angels and yet not true angels".

dvl.name: Virtue
dvl.desc:
The fifth of the nine orders of angels, also known as "The Shining Ones." 
They give hope to people through the miracles they perform. Virtue also played the role of midwife to Eve in the birthing of Cain.

dvl.name: Dominion
dvl.desc:
The fourth of the nine orders of angels.
Their duty is to oversee the other angels. Their actions are a manifestation of God's will, and they wish for their domination to be spread throughout the universe.

dvl.name: Throne
dvl.desc:
The third of the nine orders of angels.
They are the highest order of angels with physical form and also go by the names of Ofanim and Galgalim which means "wheel". They are called "the throne carriers" but in fact they themselves were vehicles resembling the modern-day tank.

dvl.name: Seraph
dvl.desc:
Of the highest order of angels.
Known as the "the burning ones," they burn with love for God and remain closest to him. The true majesty of the Seraphim cannot be conceived by the human mind, therefore takes the form of four-headed, six-winged beings when appearing before man.

dvl.name: Ares
dvl.desc: The god of war in Greek mythology, and one of the twelve Olympians. Aries is notorious for his temper and cruelty often being shunned by the other gods. In contrast the Olympian goddess of war and wisdom Athena is held in a higher regard.  Other than Apollo, he is arguably the most aesthetically pleasing to behold.

dvl.name: Wu Kong
dvl.desc: Seiten Taisei also known as Sun Wu Kong was supposedly born from a rock at the summit of the Mountain of Flowers and Fruit. He appears as a main character in the Chinese classical novel "Journey to the West" and famous for his monkey like appearance. He wreaked havoc and was punished by Buddha, but was eventually saved by a monk named Santsang and traveled with him on a journey towards enlightenment.

dvl.name: Beiji-Weng
dvl.desc: The Taoist deification of the Big Dipper. He governs death and judgement. He handles the fortunes and misfortunes of people's lives, but is known mostly for judging the fate of the deceased. He is especially feared by those who know they have sinned.

dvl.name: Susano-o
dvl.desc: A violent god of Japanese legend. Born to Izanagi and Izanami and brother of Amaterasu. Banned from Takaamagahara for uncouth behavior, he later performed heroic deeds such as slaying Orochi saving Kushinada who he then married. Soon after, he honors his sister with a godly gift, the sword of Kusanagi which he obtained from the tail of the Orochi.

dvl.name: Shiva
dvl.desc: The Hindu creator and destroyer of the world. Along with Vishnu, Shiva is one of the most revered gods in the Hindu faith. There is a belief that he will destroy the world near its end, purifying it during its reconstruction. He uses his destructive force towards demons, and bestows blessings on to those who worship him. His weapon is a trident of light, and his third eye is said to be able to set the world ablaze.

dvl.name: Makara
dvl.desc: A holy creature that carries the gods on its back in Hindu lore. It lives in rivers and lakes. It is a type of fish said to have the qualities of crocodiles, hippopotami, elephants, and Naga. In the Da Tang Xiyu Ji, a Buddhist record of the western world, it is the size of a mountain and its eyes shine like the sun.

dvl.name: Illuyanka
dvl.desc: A serpentine dragon god who ruled the seas in Hittite mythology. In ancient Near Eastern civilizations, the rough waters and river floods were often thought to be caused by mighty dragons such as Illuyanka. There are many legends about him, including a time when he fought the god of storms, showing greater power than his opponent.

dvl.name: Long
dvl.desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures in Chinese lore. The Four beasts were divided equally throughout the land to protect the five emperors in ancient China. There is even a mural depiction of them in the Kitora Tomb in Japan. Long the azure dragon is protector of the east and represents the season of spring. In Feng Shui, placing water in the east, guides Longs' power and is said to bring good fortune.

dvl.name: Gucumatz
dvl.desc: A giant monster with blue and green plumage that appears in the Popol Vuh of Mayan lore. The god of the sky Huracan and the god of the sea Gucumatz conjured mountains and land from water and gave life to the world. The ancient Mayans also called Gucumatz the god of creation for this reason.

dvl.name: Quetzalcoatl
dvl.desc: An Aztec creator god known as "the feathered serpent". He created humans from his own blood and known as the god of wind and giver of life. Quetzalcoatl is identified as the sun, and Venus is said to be his heart. Initially he was worshiped as the god of water and harvest, later recognized as the god of culture.

dvl.name: Huang Long
dvl.desc: One of the holy dragons of Chinese lore, the Golden Dragon appears in times of great fortune or joy. His dominion over the earth extends to the four gods Long, Gui Xian, Feng Huang, and Baihu.

dvl.name: Hamsa
dvl.desc:
The sacred white goose that Brahma rides in Hindu lore.
The sight of pure white flying the winter skies symbolized the efforts of the Brahmins trying to obtain Brahma's knowledge. It is said that is why Hamsa became Brahma's steed.

dvl.name: Suparna
dvl.desc: The god also known as the King of Birds from Hindu lore. Its name means "one with beautiful wings." It can create mighty winds at will, and can also change its size freely.

dvl.name: Jatayu
dvl.desc: The King of Vultures and son of the sacred bird Garuda in Indian lore. In the epic Ramayana, Jatayu aids his friend King Rama who is Vishnu incarnate. When Rama's wife Sita is kidnapped by the demon-king Ravana, Jatayu fought with all his might to save her.

dvl.name: Feng Huang
dvl.desc: One of the Ssu-Ling, celestial creatures in Chinese lore. The Four beasts were divided equally throughout the land to protect the five emperors in ancient China. There is even a mural depiction of them in the Kitora Tomb in Japan. Huang the Vermilion Bird is protector of the south and represents the season of summer. It is gigantic, resembles a quail and is said to chirp in five beautiful voices.

dvl.name: Yatagarasu
dvl.desc: A divine creature in Japanese lore. They are three-legged birds sent by Amaterasu to help humans and are said to have helped Emperor Jinmu claim victory. Because of their divinity some without faith are driven mad at their sight.

dvl.name: Garuda
dvl.desc: A gargantuan bird in Indian lore, greatest enemy of the Naga. To save his captured mother from the Naga, He stole Amrita from the gods in exchange for her freedom. Impressed, Vishnu grants Garuda immortality in exchange for becoming his steed.

dvl.name: Slime
dvl.desc: The byproduct of a failed summoning. Devoid of its original powers, it's trapped in an incomplete gel form. This is the sad excuse of what a demon becomes when its journey from the underworld Atziluth to the human world Assiah goes wrong.

dvl.name: Phantom
dvl.desc: Phantoms are spirit like beings said to appear to some in the guise of loved ones, bringing tidings of ill or good. They are often mentioned in English folklore as the vengeful ghosts of those who die with regrets.

dvl.name: Blob
dvl.desc: An amorphous gelatinous monster also known as "Shimi". Its body is a glob of bubbly blood red slime that grows ever larger with each human victim it melts to consume. It prefers warmth and humidity to the cold where it becomes sluggish. Simply freezing it will stop its movement completely.

dvl.name: Black Ooze
dvl.desc: An amorphous creature born from the evil and vile intent of a demon who failed to transform into its true form. It is simply an ever-growing black blob of viscous liquid that mindlessly devours everything in its path.

dvl.name: Shadow
dvl.desc: A ghastly being that appears in mirror image of its victims. It is rumored that within a few days, death will come to those who see them. There is much lore in multiple cultures pertaining to this phenomenon. Some say that it is a sign of mental illness.

dvl.name: Mad Gasser
dvl.desc: A mysterious tall man garbed in black that wickedly disperses an unknown poisonous gas. The inhalation of his sweetly scented concoction causes intense headaches and vomiting. He returns when people begin to forget his existence, though he is rarely seen.

dvl.name: Leanan Sidhe
dvl.desc: A beautiful fairy of Irish lore whose name means "fairy mistress." She drains the life of her lovers but in return grants them with artistic inspiration.

dvl.name: Shikome
dvl.desc: In Japanese lore, they are hideous demonesses of Yomi, the land of the dead, and serve the gods there. Izanagi came down to Yomi to take back his dead wife Izanami, but when he saw her ugly form, he tried to escape from her. Enraged, Izanami sent the Shikome after him. As he ran, Izanagi threw his hair and comb to the ground. His hair became grapes and his come bamboo sprouts that the Shikome started eating, forgetting their duty.

dvl.name: Yaksini
dvl.desc: A female demon in Hindu mythology. Once worshiped by Dravidians as the goddess of fertility, with the introduction of Hinduism and conflicting ideologies, she was rebranded a demon. Yaksini is often depicted as an attractive woman.

dvl.name: Mermaid
dvl.desc: Half-woman, half-fish creatures of the ocean. Their male counterparts are called "Mermen." Legend says they use their voices to charm men, causing them to crash their ships. Mermaids are regarded as unlucky omens by men of the sea, and are a sign of a bad catch or devastating storms.

dvl.name: Dakini
dvl.desc: Hindu deities of passion and relations. Their name means "sky dancer" and are Kali's attendants. They eat human flesh and gather at graveyards and crematories each night.

dvl.name: Rangda
dvl.desc: A wicked enchantress and the symbol of evil in Balinese Hinduism. When a witch full of hate strays from the path of good to serve evil, they become this vile creature. Rangda uses black magic to cause natural disasters, plagues, curses, and even uses evil spirits to do her bidding.

dvl.name: Take-Minakata
dvl.desc: He is a god of war, the hunt and fertility in Japanese lore. He fought Take-Mikazuchi for control of Japan and lost. Though he escaped to Shinano no Kuni he was chased and cornered. Since then, he has been forbidden to leave the land of Suwa.

dvl.name: Zouchouten
dvl.desc:
One of the Four Heavenly Kings in Buddhist faith.
He is commonly depicted wearing armor, with a sword in hand and an angry expression on his face. Zouchouten is protector of the South under the command of Sakra and is a similar being to the eight legions. He is also the god of fertility and agriculture, and affects the growth of all things.

dvl.name: Koumokuten
dvl.desc:
One of the Four Heavenly Kings in Buddhist faith.
He is commonly depicted wearing armor, with a trident in hand and an angry expression on his face. Koumokuten is protector of the West under the command of Sakra and is a similar being to the eight legions. He keeps a close watch on the world with his sharp gaze and enlightens people with his speeches.

dvl.name: Jikokuten
dvl.desc:
One of the Four Heavenly Kings in Buddhist faith.
He is commonly shown wearing armor, with a sword in hand and an angry expression on his face. Jikokuten is protector of the East under the command of Sakra and is a similar being to the eight legions. He also helps maintain the security of the nation.

dvl.name: Bishamonten
dvl.desc:
One of the Four Heavenly Kings in Buddhist faith, also known as Tamonten.
He is commonly depicted wearing armor, with a spear in hand and an angry expression on his face. Bishamonten is protector of the North under the command of Sakra and is a similar being to the eight legions. He is renowned as a war god, for even Prince Shotoku prayed to him, and later incorporated as one of the Seven Gods of Fortune, the deity that protects wealth.

dvl.name: Zhong Kui
dvl.desc: A god in Chinese lore whose mission is to vanquish evil. One day, when the Emperor Xuanzong was sick, he had a dream where an imp tried to steal his wife Yang Kuei Feis' belongings. Zhong Kui, a large man, suddenly appeared and rid the imp with ease. Miraculously after waking from the dream, the emperor was cured. As a human, Zhong Kui committed suicide after failing an exam to become an imperial official, but Emperor Gaozu gave him an honorable burial. To repay the emperor, Zhong Kui swore to rid the world of evil.

dvl.name: Thor
dvl.desc: The Norse god of thunder. Later known as the god of agriculture, he was worshipped mostly by farmers. Thor is a heroic and honest god with unrivaled strength. Some claim he could even swallow a cow whole. With the magical hammer Mjolnir which returns to its owner after being thrown, he smites his enemies with ease.

dvl.name: Kurama Tengu
dvl.desc: A type of tengu said to have lived in Mt. Kurama in Kyoto. As the most powerful and well-known of the tengu, they have the power to fend off disease and bring good fortune. Also rumored to be the incarnation of Bishamonten.

dvl.name: Tam Lin
dvl.desc: A fairy knight from Scotland. As a member of the Seelie Court, his duty is to guard the forest of Carterhaugh. When he was still a human boy, he was kidnapped by the fairy queen after fainting from an unfortunate horse riding accident. He soon learned to adopt their ways.

dvl.name: Kresnik
dvl.desc: A holy vampire hunter blessed by the light. His name means "cross." Kresnik and his rival the Slovenian vampire, Kudlak both had the power to turn into various animals. When transformed Kresnik was distinctly white and Kudlak had a darker hue. It is said that evil can never overcome light, and each battle ends with Kresnik being victorious. Nevertheless the battles between them were epic.

dvl.name: Hanuman
dvl.desc: A heroic god of Hindu lore. Often depicted as a monkey he is extremely agile and had great intelligence. His name means, "jaw." With golden skin his face shines scarlet, and he also has a long tail. As the son of the wind god Vayu, he has the power to fly and can transform into anything at will.

dvl.name: Tsukuyomi
dvl.desc: The moon god from Japanese mythology. Tsukuyomi was said to have been born from the right eye of Izanagi during purification after his escape from Yomi no kuni, the underworld. Tsukuyomi was the second of the "three noble children," who was commanded by his father Izanagi to watch over the night sky. In the Chronicles of Japan, Tsukuyomi and his sister the sun goddess Amaterasu part ways due to their disagreements. This is why the sun and moon appear at different times in the sky.

dvl.name: Cu Chulainn
dvl.desc: A gallant Celtic hero, son of the sun god Lugh. His weapon is the mighty spear Gae Bolg. His good looks could be deceiving, for in battle he is ferocious, tearing down his enemies and wiping out entire armies.

dvl.name: Abraxas
dvl.desc: Originally the all mighty being in Gnosticism, was later regarded as a fallen angel in Christian Orthodoxy. Wielding a whip in one hand and shield in the other he has the head of a rooster and lower body of a snake. The physical world was created by Abraxas, but it is prophesized that on the day of judgement this too will disappear from existence. His figure is often carved into gems and stones as charms known as "Abraxas Stones".

dvl.name: Baphomet
dvl.desc: A goat-headed demon that governs Black Masses. His name is sometimes used as a catch-all term for demons in general. During the Inquisition of the Templar Knights, this name was mentioned as the evil that was worshiped at the time. Witches are known to worship him as well.

dvl.name: Arahabaki
dvl.desc: One of the chief gods of ancient Japanese lore. His image is reflected in Shakoukidogu statues. Because he was worshipped by Nagasunehiko, who defeated Emperor Jimmu's army, he was seen as a symbol of rebellion toward the Emperor, causing his adherents to be persecuted.

dvl.name: Pazuzu
dvl.desc: A demon lord of southeast winds and scorching sands from Sumerian lore. He's a vile demon with the head and arms of a lion, the body of a human, birdlike wings, hawk like talons, a poisonous tail like a scorpion, and a strange horn protruding from his forehead. Pazuzu rides the warm winds from the Persian Gulf spreading diseases that can only be cured by magical means.

dvl.name: Girimekhala
dvl.desc: A gargantuan elephant monster of Sri Lankan lore. It is typically portrayed as being ridden by the demon Mara. Whoever looks into its evil eye is said to be met with misfortune.

dvl.name: Seth
dvl.desc: The Egyptian god of evil, the desert, lightning and storms. He murdered his brother Osiris and tried to become chief of the gods, but was soon overthrown by Osiris' son, Horus. Seth moved on to be worshiped by more accepting people away from the Nile River.

dvl.name: Hathor
dvl.desc: The Egyptian goddess of fertility. She is also the goddess of love, motherhood, joy, and even guardian of the mines, making her one of the most worshiped of the gods. She appears to have seven different guises, but is often depicted as a cow carrying the disc of the sun.

dvl.name: Arianrhod
dvl.desc: A Welsh goddess of the moon also known as Arianfuroddo. Arian means "silver" and furoddo means "wheel". Her wheel was said to be used to ferry the dead to the afterlife. The moon symbolizes death and regeneration, which is why she is also highly worshiped as the goddess of rebirth. There are some who hold festivities at the full moon to praise her.

dvl.name: Scathach
dvl.desc: The war goddess of Celtic lore, as well as the queen of the Land of Shadows. She is a skilled magician and a master warrior. She trains young men who come to her in the art of war. The famed Cu Chulainn was one of her students, gifting him with the legendary Gae Bolg once he mastered her teachings.

dvl.name: Pallas Athena
dvl.desc: The goddess of war in Greek mythology and one of the twelve Olympian gods. She sprung from Zeus' forehead fully armored after he swallowed her mother, Metis. She is also considered the goddess of skill and art, and though she is the goddess of war, would only engage in battle to protect that which she loves and never for the sake of warfare.

dvl.name: Sarasvati
dvl.desc: The goddess of knowledge and wisdom in Hindu lore, and the wife of Brahma. Also as the goddess of music and arts, she is skilled in every art known to man, often depicted holding the lute. Her name means "the one who flows" for she is the incarnation of a river.

dvl.name: Ishtar
dvl.desc: The goddess of love and war, worshiped in ancient Mesopotamia, also called "the queen of the heavens". In the "Epic of Gilgamesh" she is depicted as a woman with many suiters, charming the hearts of heroes, then turning them into beasts and slaughtering them when she had her fun.

dvl.name: Lakshmi
dvl.desc: The goddess of beauty and good fortune in Hindu lore. Vishnu's wife and Kama's mother, she is the goddess of love. She is the embodiment of beauty and is unrivaled. Lakshmi is a fabulous dancer, charming even the gods with her enchanting moves.

dvl.name: Izanami
dvl.desc: A goddess in Japanese mythology known as "Mother Earth". She gave birth to the islands with her husband Izanagi. She mothered many gods, but she died from burns birthing the fire god Hinokagutsuchi. Izanagi traveled to Yomi no kuni to bring her back to the land of the living, but when he saw her changed and deformed, he ran in fear. Afterwards, Izanami became the goddess of the dead, Yomotsu-Okami.

dvl.name: Melchom
dvl.desc: The accountant of hell often depicted as a demon holding a wallet. He is said to be the official in charge of the chamberlains' expenses. It is certain that Melchom hands out the paychecks of hells' public servants, but the rest of his duties remain a mystery.

dvl.name: Eligor
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. He appears as a knight holding a lance or pennon. The story goes that when Eligor is called upon in battle, he will see through the enemy plans and predict the moves that are to come.

dvl.name: Decarabia
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. This odd demon usually appears as a pentagram, but can show himself in human form if his summoner wishes. He holds great knowledge in the hidden powers of plants and stone. Decarabia is known to gift his summoner with command of bird familiars.

dvl.name: Forneus
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. When summoned it appears as a large winged fish or similar sea creature. This creature is especially well versed, teaching its summoner the art of rhetoric. One who masters Forneus' craft is able to convince even the most stubborn minds.

dvl.name: Ose
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. He has the power to reveal truths and fill his summoners enemies with blind rage. Ose can also change a person to their desired look, but as a consequence that person will not realize the transformation took place.

dvl.name: Dantalian
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. He is a duke with many faces that change constantly. He holds a heavy book in his right hand which has the thoughts of all living beings, past, present, and future, written in a language only he can read.

dvl.name: Samael
dvl.desc: A mysterious angel whose name means "poison of God." Though an angel, he is considered the leader of demons, often depicted as a large winged serpent. Opinions differ on whether he is one of the fallen or not.

dvl.name: Lucifer
dvl.desc: The one who rules hell and all of its inhabitance, formerly known as the archangel of light. His name means "morning star" and before he fell, was the chief of the Seraphim. With a third of Gods angels on his side, Lucifer rebelled against God. He was defeated by Gods superior forces however, and in hell awaits his chance to strike again.

dvl.name: Horkos
dvl.desc: A demon in Greek mythology, and king of the vile Orcs. In the middle ages pigs were often used in animal sacrifice, which may be why he is often depicted with a hogs' head.

dvl.name: Abaddon
dvl.desc: Lord of the abyss in the Book of Revelation, the source of evil and cause of plagues. He leads the seventh order of demons who appear at the sounding of the fifth trumpet on Judgement Day, when he will command a horde of locusts wreaking havoc and suffering. His name means "destroyer" and "endless pit" and even considered the abyss itself.

dvl.name: King Frost
dvl.desc: The king of snow. He is a snowman large and proud, ruling and commanding the infinite number of Jack Frosts. King Frost retains the ability to freeze the world over entirely but as are the Jack Frosts, he is a bit innocent and naive.

dvl.name: Beelzebub
dvl.desc: The King of Hell, known as "Lord of the Flies." By making them carry the souls of the dead, he keeps the flies he rules in order. In the Bible he is mentioned as one of the most formidable demons of high rank. It is also said that he was once the lord Baal of Canaan who was punished and became Beelzebub.

dvl.name: Loki
dvl.desc: An evil god of Norse mythology known as the trickster. Loki was born to the giants, archenemies of the gods. Thanks to a treaty that Odin, lord of the gods, made with the giants, Loki was permitted to join the ranks of the gods. He was said to look cunning, attracting many. At times he would even transform into a woman to have a male mate. Though he is the cause of much strife, he is known to be the hero in some situations which make him a peculiar and intriguing god.

dvl.name: Surt
dvl.desc: A fire giant in Norse lore. He rules the fire realm, Muspelheim, and brandishes the burning sword Laevateinn. At Ragnarok, he will set the world ablaze.

dvl.name: Mara
dvl.desc: The hard bringer of death. A Hindu demon that dominates spirits, and holds the power to instill fear. During his meditations, Buddha almost gave in to his temptation when Mara seduced him under a linden, a hardwood tree. Maras' great power was a sight to behold. His rigid strength spread far and wide, giving birth to many vile creatures.

dvl.name: Cu Sith
dvl.desc: A fairy of Scottish legend that takes the form of a dog, "Cu" meaning dog and "Sith", fairy. When the Cu Sith hunts, its bark is so loud it reaches the ends of the horizon making its prey cower in fear.

dvl.name: Inugami
dvl.desc: A dog spirit said to possess people in Japanese lore. Those possessed are put in a state of "inu-tsuki," and lose consciousness. There tends to be more lore about the Inugami in areas where the fox, which is an animal in folklore that is treated in a similar manner, is not common. Onmyoji used them as familiars.

dvl.name: Nekomata
dvl.desc: A cat yokai in Japanese folklore. Long-lived cats are said to become these creatures that have mastered human speech. The powers of the Nekomata vary, some were even strong enough to turn into people or command the dead.

dvl.name: Orthrus
dvl.desc: A great two-headed dog in Greek mythology, with a mane and tail of snakes. Orthrus guarded the herds of the monster Geryon, who lived on the island of Erytheia at the edge of the world. However, he was killed by a blow from the club of Heracles, who came to the island as part of his Twelve Labors.

dvl.name: Ammut
dvl.desc: A creature of Egyptian lore with the head of a crocodile, the front legs of a lion, and the hind legs of a hippo. When a person dies, he must be judged by Osiris. His heart is weighed on a scale, and if the heart is heavier than the feather of truth, the heart is given to Ammut to devour, denying the dead of eternal life. His name means "the one who greedily devours".

dvl.name: Cerberus
dvl.desc: A large three-headed beast from Greek mythology, guard dog of the gateway to the underworld and often depicted with a snake for a tail. Born to the giant of wind Typhon and the snake Echidna, its brother is Orthrus.

dvl.name: Horus
dvl.desc: The Egyptian god of the sky. The son of Osiris and Isis, he represents the falcon and other great symbols. In certain areas and eras he is recognized as the sun or chief of the gods.

dvl.name: Mitra
dvl.desc: A god of the sun and war in Zoroastrian lore, and also recognized as the god of contracts and fraternity. He punishes those who are corrupt and is known to cure disease, sustaining harmony and truth on earth.

dvl.name: Prometheus
dvl.desc: A Titan in Greek mythology, his name means "foresee." The Titans were the race of giants who ruled the world before the great Olympian gods. Prometheus is well known for stealing fire from the gods and giving it to mankind.

dvl.name: Odin
dvl.desc: A Great warrior and magician, seeker of wisdom and the chief of the Norse gods. He willingly sacrificed an eye to drink from the Well of Wisdom. As the chief of the gods, Odin will gladly welcome anyone with a warrior spirit.

dvl.name: Amaterasu
dvl.desc: The Japanese goddess of the sun and light. She is one of the chief deities of Takaamagahara, the land of the Amatsu gods. Her most known tale is the time the world was shrouded in darkness when she withdrew into Amano-iwato, annoyed at her brother Susano-os' fit of rage. As does the Ise Shrine, many worship her as the goddess of nature.

dvl.name: Vishnu
dvl.desc: One of the primary gods in the Hindu lore. He is called "the preserver" and the incarnation of sun light. Appearing in different locations in one of his ten "Avatar" forms, he saves the world from danger and restores peace.

dvl.name: Mokoi
dvl.desc: An evil spirit from Australian Aboriginal mythology. It lives in the jungle and looks human, but it cannot speak for it has no tongue. It is known to kill those under the influence of black magic.

dvl.name: Sandman
dvl.desc: A fairy in German folklore. He cannot be seen by human eyes but is rumored to carry a bag of magical sand, which puts humans to sleep when thrown into their eyes. If the victim resists, the Sandman will sit on their eyelids forcing them to sleep.

dvl.name: Incubus
dvl.desc: Originating in European folklore, the Incubus is the male counterpart to the Succubus. It ravishes women in their dreams, impregnating them. The children between an Incubus and a human become demons or similar ilk.

dvl.name: Fomorian
dvl.desc: Evil giants of Celtic lore and rivals to the Tuatha Dé Danann. They are often depicted as goat- or horse-headed barbarians. They were led by lord Balor of the Evil Eye to repel their enemy invaders of the west.

dvl.name: Kaiwan
dvl.desc: Written in the Book of Amos, the Old Testament as the one who was worshiped by the Israelites before the heavenly lord was accepted. He is associated with the stars and often assimilated with Sakkutthe god of Saturn and was once called the god of the sky.

dvl.name: Lilim
dvl.desc:
The daughters of Lilith, the first wife of Adam, sired by demons in the Old Testament.
They are seducers preying upon men preferably of the Clergy, creeping into their dreams. As their mother they are identified with the succubi, feared as the evil temptation that lurks by.

dvl.name: Succubus
dvl.desc: Originating in European folklore, the Succubus is the female counterpart to the Incubus. They visit men in their dreams sucking the life force out of them. They appear as great beauties in dreams, but in fact are ugly hags.

dvl.name: Lilith
dvl.desc: Adam's first wife in the Old Testament. She became a demon after leaving Eden. There are various theories as to how she fell, but all agree she is an iconic adulteress. When she rebelled against God, she was cursed to have a snake's tail instead of legs, and often depicted as such.

dvl.name: Preta
dvl.desc: Known as Gaki in Japanese, they are ghoulish demons of Buddhist lore. Greedy humans cast into the Preta realm become these unfortunate creatures. Any food they try to consume burns up in their mouth, fated to be tormented by never ending hunger and thirst.

dvl.name: Obariyon
dvl.desc: A Japanese "piggyback monster" that jumps on to people's backs as they walk along grassy paths. It is heavy and not easy to carry. Many people give up and flee, but if you can take it back home, it will reward you by turning into gold coins.

dvl.name: Mou-Ryo
dvl.desc: A spirit of the dead that failed to ascend to the heavens in Japanese lore. Some have evil intent, but most are not that powerful. They are often depicted as flaming balls.

dvl.name: Pisaca
dvl.desc: A type of Preta in Hindu lore that eats human corpses. It enters a human through the mouth and causes harm to its host until expelled. Those who see one are said to die within nine months.

dvl.name: Legion
dvl.desc: The spirit who said, "For we are many" in scripture. A conglomerate of evil spirits that experienced similar pains. The evil spirit sees other spirits suffering as their own, melding themselves together to truly become one.

dvl.name: Chatterskull
dvl.desc: A sentient skull from Dominican folklore. Those who hear its high-pitched screeching laugh are doomed to have a bone chilling death.

dvl.name: Vetala
dvl.desc: A type of Preta in Hindu and Buddhist lore. Vetala are considered the greatest and most dangerous of all Preta. They lurk in graveyards reanimating corpses to do their bidding, attacking humans until everything and everyone is mangled.

dvl.name: Azumi
dvl.desc:
A god from Japanese lore that can control water. Barnacles and algae cover its body. 
The Azumi fishing tribe that came from the south claim to be descended from it. The Azumi tribe's ancestors are said to be the three gods born to Izanagi after returning from Yomi no kuni.

dvl.name: Momunofu
dvl.desc: A war god in ancient Japanese lore and one of Arahabaki's subordinates. The character Momotaro from old fairytale is said to be modeled after him, and his name is the origin for the word "mononofu" the Japanese word for "warrior." The ancient Mononobe warrior clan would call their gifted children Momunofu in his name.

dvl.name: Oni
dvl.desc: An evil monster of Japanese lore known to plunder and massacre villages with their massive iron clubs. They have horns on their heads, long claws, and razor-sharp teeth. They are usually a red or blue color appearing in countless tales.

dvl.name: Ikusa
dvl.desc: A demon soldier in the Yomi army from Japanese lore. He loyally serves the gods of Yomi no kuni. When Izanagi tried to rescue his wife Izanami from Yomi, Ikusa was one of the monsters sent to chase after Izanagi when he realized Izanami had become a hideous hag.

dvl.name: Shiki-Ouji
dvl.desc: A Shikigami conjured by Onmyoji with the power to heal or inflict pain and suffering. It usually takes the form of a paper doll or animal, but can change its shape freely. Those who touch it will fall victim to its curse.

dvl.name: Berserker
dvl.desc: Fierce Norse warriors who fight heedlessly and without fear. In battle their blood boils, attacking friend and foe with blind ferocity. Their name comes from the bearskin coats they adorn and are the warriors of Odin.

dvl.name: Ongyo-Ki
dvl.desc: One of the four oni controlled by Fujiwara no Chikata in the Heian period. It is extremely adept at hiding its presence, striking enemies from the shadows. The Ninjas where modeled after this demon.

dvl.name: Chagrin
dvl.desc: An evil spirit of Gypsy lore, also called Chagrino or Harginn. As the Romani Gypsies roved, the lore of this creature evolved; absorbing traits from other cultures and religions giving it a unique background. The Chargrin appears as a yellow hedgehog and those who chase after it will be cursed.

dvl.name: Bicorn
dvl.desc: A horse like beast with two helical horns on its head. While the Unicorn represents purity the Bicorn is its opposite. Its origin is unclear but some believe it is derived from Re'em, the dual-horned beast in the Old Testament

dvl.name: Raiju
dvl.desc: A beast of Japanese lore, said to come down to Earth on a bolt of lightning. It is about 2 feet (60 centimeters) long, with ferret like claws and lives running around in thunder clouds. Other details about the Raiju are depicted slightly differently depending on where the story originates.

dvl.name: Nue
dvl.desc: A creature of Japanese lore. It has the head of a monkey, the legs of a tiger, and the tail of a snake. In a story in the Tale of the Heike, it hid behind a black cloud and attacked the emperor, but it was slain by a famous shogun warrior.

dvl.name: Mothman
dvl.desc: A cryptid sighted in the USA from the 1960s to 1980s. It has red, shining eyes and was known for the finlike appendages on the sides of its body. It's said to walk on two feet and fly without moving its appendages. It can keenly sense blood to track its source and feed on it. Eyewitnesses say that a UFO was sighted when Mothman appeared, so some believe that it is actually an alien.

dvl.name: Peallaidh
dvl.desc: Half-human, half-beast sprites of Scotland that live by the water, lakes, rivers, and seashores. They are part of a group of fairies known as Urisks. The Peallaidh have the top half of a hairy man, the legs of a deer, and the hooves of a goat. When lonely, they chase after travelers.

dvl.name: Fenrir
dvl.desc: A giant wolf beast of Nordic lore, son of the evil god Loki. In fear of Fenrir's ever-growing stature, the gods bind him with the magical rope Gleipnir. However, at Ragnarok his magical bindings will be broken and he will rise against the Aesir in combat.

dvl.name: Pixie
dvl.desc: Small fairies found in southwest Britain. They are cheerful and like to play pranks. Their physical appearance changes from region to region and they always act mischievously. Though they love pranking the common folk, they are known to aid farmers and are generally considered good fairies.

dvl.name: Party Pixie
dvl.desc: Pixies that love festivities. They appear during all joyous occasions to put people in a cheery mood. Their mischievous nature, however, remains. It is said that unsuspecting victims often find themselves whisked off to unexpected places with hazy memories, or that they become far more talkative than normal.

dvl.name: Jack Frost
dvl.desc: Frost spirits that appear during the winter and melt away in spring. They are made of ice and snow, but do not be fooled by their cute demeanor. Jack Frosts freeze people with their cold breath, smiling all the while. They originally were ugly creatures but changed in order to let their victims' guard down.

dvl.name: Party Frost
dvl.desc:
A Jack Frost that loves parties and celebrations.
Tends to appear, seemingly out of nowhere, on cold winter days, especially if there's some kind of celebration going on.
At first only reveling in the festive atmosphere, Party Frost soon discovered it could freeze large crowds of humans effortlessly when they gathered. Emitting waves of intense cold, it reportedly left countless people frozen in place, their smiles still on their faces.

dvl.name: Pyro Jack
dvl.desc: British fire spirits, also known as Jack O'Lantern. Will-o'-the-Wisps were the first of its kind, originating in the Cornwall region, and were believed to be the wandering spirits of the dead. They are commonly known to appear during the Halloween festivities. Pyro Jacks often come out at night to startle travelers and make them lose their way.

dvl.name: Halloween Jack
dvl.desc:
A Pyro Jack that found itself mixed up with the Liberators' Halloween costume party.
It originally planned a party of its own - one that involved opening a gate between this world and the spirit world, letting hordes of demons loose to wreak terror - until the Liberators put a stop to it. Wanting only to enjoy good times with friends, it became an ally of the Liberators after experiencing their Halloween costume party.

dvl.name: Helper Frost
dvl.desc:
A Jack Frost that’s a big fan of Santa Claus.
Upon encountering Meat Balloon on a cold winter’s day, Jack Frost mistakes him for Santa and decides to help out. It tries giving presents to each of the Liberators but fails to get them what they want. After being consoled by Meat Balloon, Jack Frost realizes the true meaning of Christmas and decides to become his helper in the hopes of becoming Santa Clause itself someday.

dvl.name: High Pixie
dvl.desc: One of a higher class of pixie, these are the Seelie Court's more powerful soldiers. They are charged with guarding the ruins and caves where other pixies dwell.

dvl.name: Kelpie
dvl.desc: A fairy of Celtic folklore that lives by the water that looks like a horse. It is friendly at first goading you to ride it, but tries to drown those who do. Once tamed, it is a mightily loyal steed.

dvl.name: Silky
dvl.desc: A house fairy of England and Scotland. She carries out household chores while everyone sleeps and is a welcome spirit. It is said you can hear her silk skirts rustle as she works. However, she will kill anyone who tries to cause harm to the family she protects.

dvl.name: Setanta
dvl.desc: A brave young hero in Celtic lore. He was attacked by a vicious guard dog when he arrived at Chulainn manor, killing it with his bare hands. He took up its role as guardian, and adopted the name "Cu Chulainn," meaning "Culann's Hound" and swore to serve and protect until a replacement was sired.

dvl.name: Titania
dvl.desc: The queen of the fairies and wife of King Oberon. She is based on the Roman goddess Diana. With her faithful flower pixies by her side, she gathers magic from moonlight. And is well known for her role as the fairy queen in Shakespeare's "A Midsummer Night's Dream.

dvl.name: Oberon
dvl.desc: The king of the fairies and the husband of Titania. He is quite old, but due to a curse he received as a child, he remains young and beautiful. Oberon is magically gifted with the power to influence the minds of men and place them under his control.

dvl.name: Agathion
dvl.desc: A familiar with no corporeal form. There is no consensus on the actual appearance of an Agathion. When summoned they may resemble a human, bird, or animal. They are usually sealed away in bottles or pots, but can also inhabit rings or talismans. The word Agathion is also used as a general term for familiars.

dvl.name: Koppa Tengu
dvl.desc: A type of Tengu that dwells in the deepest forests. Their spiritual power is weaker than other tengu, which make them smaller in stature. When the time comes, long-lived wolves transform into this form that closely resembles the Karasu Tengu.

dvl.name: Apsaras
dvl.desc:
Water spirits in Hindu lore. Their name means "those who move in the water."
They appear as young women with enchanting beauty often used as a symbol of temptation. Apsaras are known to carry the souls of those who die in battle to heaven, where Indra, the god of thunder, awaits them.

dvl.name: Dis
dvl.desc:
The general term for low-ranking deities in Norse mythology or a kind of spirit.
They are said to bring good luck in battle and also represent fate, fertility and good harvest. Some view them as the servants of the Valkyrie.

dvl.name: Valkyrie
dvl.desc: Odin's daughters in Norse lore. From their flying steeds they fight with vigor. They dutifully guide the souls of fallen warriors to Valhalla in preparation for Ragnarok.

dvl.name: Efreet
dvl.desc: A powerful fire spirit in Arabian lore. The Efreet will bring great fortune to those whom it deems worthy. Though it is easily upset and will crush its summoner if irritated. It is well known for its appearance in the book "Arabian Nights".

dvl.name: Ganesha
dvl.desc: A god of wisdom and good luck in Indian mythology, often depicted with an elephants head. He is said to protect against disasters, bestow wisdom, and bring wealth and fortune therefore loved and widely worshiped especially by merchants. Ganesha was originally created by Parvati from her own filth to guard against Shiva her husband from peeking as she bathed. But when Shiva returned one day to find his path blocked by Ganesha, he cut the youth's head off, not knowing who he was. Seeing this, Parvati was stricken with grief, and Shiva, in panic, cut off the head of a passing elephant and placed it on Ganesha's shoulders.

dvl.name: Nozuchi
dvl.desc: A snake spirit said to live in the mountains in ancient Japanese lore. It is not evil, but has a violent temper and sometimes eats humans that cross its path. It is said to have no eyes nor nose, but have a huge protruding mouth.

dvl.name: Naga
dvl.desc: Snake gods of Indian mythology, depicted as being half-snake and half-human. They are regarded as gods of rebirth or reincarnation. The Naga live at the bottom of lakes, in rivers and oceans. When they are not at war, they live a joyful life singing and dancing.

dvl.name: Gui Xian
dvl.desc: One of the Ssu Ling, celestial creatures in Chinese lore. The Four beasts were divided equally throughout the land to protect the five emperors in ancient China. There is even a mural depiction of them in the Kitora Tomb in Japan. Gui Xian the turtle is protector of the north and represents the season of winter. It gives guidance based on the future it foresees and will even fight against evil in the guise of a human.

dvl.name: Orochi
dvl.desc: An eight-headed and eight-tailed serpent from Japanese lore. It's said that trees and moss grow on its body and its belly ever wet with human blood. Every year it demanded a maiden for sacrifice but was tricked and slain by the mighty Susano-o. The sword of Kusanagi was obtained by Susano-o from the tail of the Orochi.

dvl.name: Yurlungur
dvl.desc: A great copper snake from Murngin lore. As a god of harvest he controls the weather. He resides in a holy pond filled with rainbow-colored water giving him the name "Rainbow Serpent".

dvl.name: Ananta
dvl.desc: A serpent with 1,000 heads in Hindu lore. This god will appear in the beginning and end of a world. Ananta is Sanskrit for "infinite." After resting on him, Vishnu woke up and created the universe.

dvl.name: White Rider
dvl.desc: One of the four horsemen in the Book of Revelation. He wears a crown rides a white horse and is tasked to bring undeniable victory. The four horsemen have the power to conquer and kill and often thought to bring chaos.

dvl.name: Hell Biker
dvl.desc: Clothed all in black, a red scarf streaming, he rides full of rage calling himself the "Angel of Hell". His strong hate for the world and himself turned him into this vile demon whose violent hatred is infectious.

dvl.name: Alice
dvl.desc: A ghost who appears as a small blonde girl. Contrary to how she looks, her magical powers are formidable. Some say she is the ghost of an English girl who suffered a gruesome death. Others claim she was born from the twisted desires of a disturbed writer's mind, alas not even she can recall the truth.

dvl.name: Trumpeter
dvl.desc: Angels with trumpets that appear in the Book of Revelation. As their trumpets sound the stars will fall, fire and disaster will consume the earth as it turns into a living hell.

dvl.name: Huang Di
dvl.desc: The Yellow Emperor of China, one of the Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors in ancient Chinese lore. He is known as the creator or inventor. He created culture itself, gifting people with shelter, clothes, vehicles, music, medicine and many other great advancements.

dvl.name: Yoshitsune
dvl.desc: A Japanese Shogun in the late Heian era. Younger brother of Minamoto No Yoritomo, and well known for his childhood name Ushiwakamaru. With his brother he won great glory as he finally defeated the Taira clan at the battle of Dan-no-Ura.

dvl.name: Jeanne d'Arc
dvl.desc: The girl who became the hero of France appearing near the end of the Hundred Years War, also known as "the Maid of Orleans." After praying to God for victory, she drove the English out of Orleans. However she was later captured at Compienge and was burned at the stake. Years later her conviction was overturned, and was canonized.

dvl.name: Siegfried
dvl.desc: The name of the hero in the German epic poem Nibelungenlied. He became invincible but for a spot on his back when he was bathed in the blood of a legendary dragon he slayed. In exchange for his sisters' hand in marriage, the king of Burgundy asked Siegfried to help him trick Brunnhilde the queen of Iceland to marry him. Though successful when Brunnhilde found out about the deception years later, she killed Siegfried out of spite.

dvl.name: Rama
dvl.desc: A prince of Kosala and the seventh avatar of Vishnu. He is the protagonist of the epic poem, the Ramayana. In the story he shows great valor saving his wife and killing the evil demon Ravana. His serious but earnest demeanor made him a popular hero in India.

dvl.name: Kamiotoko
dvl.desc: Beings devoid of time or space they pop into existence and attack for no good reason. Their name means "biting man" but in fact, have no corporeal form and is unclear if they are even male. They are notoriously known to leave unusual bite makes on their victims and a puddle of pungently smelling blue goo, doing their name justice.

dvl.name: Chupacabra
dvl.desc: A mysterious creature that appears in Puerto Rico that sucks the blood of cows and goats. Its name means "goat-sucker," and it resembles a kangaroo with three sharp claws on both arms and legs like a goat. It can even change color blending into its surroundings. Some speculate that it is not of this world due to the UFO citing in correlation with the Chupacabra.

dvl.name: Hare of Inaba
dvl.desc: Known in Japanese as "Inaba no Shirousagi," it is a smart rabbit written of in old tales, worshipped as a hare god. Wanting to cross the sea from Oki Island to the mainland, he had sharks line up in a row and crossed, pretending to help count them. But when he crossed and revealed that he was just using them, the sharks skinned him. Later he learned the arts of healing from the deity Ōkuninushi, and cured himself.

dvl.name: Kanbari
dvl.desc: The Japanese god of toilets, his full name is Kanbari Nyudo. He keeps the toilets horror-free, and if you recite the words "Kanbari Nyudo hototogisu" in the toilet on New Year's Eve, you won't have to worry about seeing monsters in the toilet for the next year.

dvl.name: Kinmamon
dvl.desc: The head god of Ryukyu Shintoism. He comes from the eternal kingdom Nirai Kanai and has protected the Ryukyu Islands. There is a Yin and Yang side to this deity; the part that came from the sky is Kiraikanaino Kinmamon, and the part that came from the seas is Ohokakerakuno Kinmamon. He is known to appear before people by possessing women.

dvl.name: Kama
dvl.desc: The Hindu god of sexual desire. He is depicted as a handsome young man riding  a parrot. It is said that those who are struck by the flowered arrows of Kama will fall in love. When Kama shot Shiva during his meditations, Shiva in rage burned him with his third eye.

dvl.name: Attis
dvl.desc: A god of Phrygian lore. He watches over the growth of plants and is a symbol of rebirth. Attis who was very beautiful, was sacrificed to the goddess Cybel. Later he was idolized by the people as their savior.

dvl.name: Patrimpas
dvl.desc: The god of land, harvest, water and the sea. One of the three main gods of Lithuanian lore, usually depicted as as young man wearing a crown made of wheat.  It is said that he is the provider of all things necessary to live. This may be because he is the god of water which brings life to most things.

dvl.name: Kabuso
dvl.desc:
A demon of Ishikawa prefecture that takes the form of a kitten and is said to often bewitch people.
Because it has a wide-ended tail and lives in aquatic regions, it is 
thought to be a type of Kappa. It loves to fool people with illusions that cause them to wrestle with boulders and tree roots, or it may transform into a beautiful woman to seduce them.

dvl.name: Jack the Ripper
dvl.desc: A serial killer who terrorized London in the 19th century. He killed prostitute after prostitute in the slums of London, then mutilated their bodies. The media was quick to cover the murders, and the case was the talk of the town. Scotland Yard came up with a few suspects after a thorough investigation, but the case went unsolved. This unusual case still piques the imagination today, with aspiring detectives coming up with their own theories. The word Jack is also used not as a name but as a general term referring to a non-distinct male person.

dvl.name: Nadja
dvl.desc:
A mysterious fairy girl with green eyes and brown skin, wearing a short, white dress and a bone necklace.
She is known to show extreme devotion, especially to those she falls in love with, going above and beyond even if it puts herself in harm's way.
Her name may have come from the Russian word for hope, "Nadezda," or the English/French name stemming from it, "Nadia." Or it may have come from the young woman who appears in the eponymous novel by the French author, Andre Breton, but there is no definitive answer.

dvl.name: Alilat
dvl.desc: The Arabian mother goddess. She was thought to reside in the Black Stone at Kaaba. She and her son, Dusura the god of stars and mountains, were worshipped there by desert nomads. She was also thought of as the deity of wine.

dvl.name: Mishaguji
dvl.desc: A native Japanese god worshipped widely around the Shinano region from before the Yamato administration took control. Many places in Japan that include the word "Shakuji" are said to be named in tribute to this god.

dvl.name: Dionysus
dvl.desc: The Greek god of wine, theater and fertility. Also known as Bacchus, he was fervently worshiped by women. He is known for his teachings of grape harvesting, wine making and the widespread teachings of the cult of Dionysus.

dvl.name: Reiko Kashima
dvl.desc:
A Japanese ghost from urban legend who is usually depicted without legs. 
She is said to appear before those who by any means hear her story.
If she appears, she will ask questions like "Where are my legs?" Answer correctly and she will then ask "Who did you hear this from?" At any point if you answer her questions incorrectly, she will remove you limbs or simply kill you.

dvl.name: Mother Harlot
dvl.desc:
A demoness also known as the Whore of Babylon in the Book of Revelation.
She rides a great red beast with ten horns and seven heads, and holds a foul golden goblet. There is a detailed description of her in Revelation 17. It is said that the heads and the horns represent "kings," and describes her as "the great city that rules over the kings of the earth." This imagery has been interpreted as an allegory of the Roman Empire.

dvl.name: Daisoujou
dvl.desc: A monk who died fasting for the salvation of the masses in a time of war and despair. His spiritual power allows his body to exist without decay. It is believed that he will appear to lend a helping hand to the faithful suffering.

dvl.name: Matador
dvl.desc: A master sportsman who entertains the audience at the risk of his own life in a show where one mistake can mean death. It is said that this apparition was born from the lament of those who died performing, and fueled by the desire to please the crowd.

dvl.name: Black Frost
dvl.desc:
A Jack Frost that has grown immensely powerful and wickedly evil.
Jack Frosts are peaceable winter fairy pranksters, but when they go too far, honing their evil skills and immersing themselves in the dark arts, they become this heinous creature.

dvl.name: Hecatoncheires
dvl.desc: Giants born from Uranus and Gaia. With 50 heads and 100 arms, their name means "those with 100 arms." During the war of the Titans, Zeus freed them from Tartarus to help him obtain victory.

dvl.name: Kudlak
dvl.desc:
A vampire that represents evil and darkness who opposes Kresnik, he that is blessed by light.
It is said that all bad things, including disease, poor harvests, and bad luck, are due to Kudlak. He transforms into various animal forms to better fight Kresnik, however these other forms always seem to have a black hue.

dvl.name: Grendel
dvl.desc:
A hideous giant with great claws from the poem "Beowulf."
Irked by the boisterous bellows ringing from the hall of King Hrothgar, he attacked, ferociously killing many of Hrothgar's men.
Hearing of the evil deeds of Grendel, the hero Beowulf took up arms, slaying the foul creature in an arduous battle.

dvl.name: Rakshasa
dvl.desc:
Demons of Hindu lore that appear on moonless nights.
They are feared for being deformed and hideous, but are actually shape shifters, changing their appearance at will to deceive people.

dvl.name: Ippon-Datara
dvl.desc:
A monster with one eye and one leg, said to live deep in the mountains of Japan, though its appearance varies from story to story.
On the snowy paths of Mt. Kumano a trail of single footprints is the only evidence of its existence.

dvl.name: Gremlin
dvl.desc: Mischievous fairies that like to wreak havoc on machines and tools. It is said that during World War II, Gremlins were found when examining aircraft engine failures. They are troublesome creatures but are known to be useful at times, and are said to have helped Benjamin Franklin collect electricity from lightning.

dvl.name: Zaou-Gongen
dvl.desc: A saint that originated in Japan and is believed to be a fusion of Buddha, Guanyin and Maitreya. Zaou-Gongen was created as a part of Kinpussen belief system before the Nara period.

dvl.name: Parvati
dvl.desc:
The most worshipped goddess in Hindu religion, Parvati is a representation of beauty and virtue.
It is said that Shiva once had a wife named Sati, and when she died she was reborn as Parvati to become Shiva's wife again.
But Parvati was often neglected by the meditative Shiva, so one day she covered up Shiva's eyes during his meditation, causing him to open his third eye.

dvl.name: Cybele
dvl.desc:
A mother goddess that originated in Phrygia, she is considered to be an equivalent to the goddess Rhea after being incorporated into Greek culture.
Cybele is also known for her relationship with the beautiful youth Attis, whom she fell in love with but his disloyalty drove her mad.
Being the mistress of animals, lions are often depicted at the sides of her throne or drawing her chariot.

dvl.name: Baal
dvl.desc:
A god of storm and rain worshipped in the Canaan region, his name means "Lord" in ancient Semitic. Like his title, he is the chief deity in Ugaritic mythology.
After being incorporated into Egyptian mythology, he is equated with the storm god Seth, and is depicted in a similar fashion.

dvl.name: Mot
dvl.desc: A god of Ugaritic mythology that is the personification of death and desolation and is considered to be the lord of the underworld. He is also the counterpart of the head Ugaritic god Baal. Mot killed Baal who never approved of him but was killed in turn by his sister, Anat. It is said that when Baal was revived due to Anat's victory over Mot, Mot also came back to life.

dvl.name: Ixtab
dvl.desc: The Mayan goddess of suicide. She is said to guide the souls of deceased members of the priesthood, victims of sacrifice and war, and those who committed suicide, to live in luxury for ever under the shade of Yaxche.

dvl.name: Nergal
dvl.desc: The god of Sumerian lore who represents war, plague, floods and most ills. When the gods held a gathering, he refused to kneel to the messenger of Ereshkigal, goddess of the underworld, who summoned him soon afterwards. He took 14 guards given to him by his father Ea, with the full intention of killing Ereshkigal. However, she promised to become his wife and give him control over the underworld, so he spared her life.

dvl.name: Persephone
dvl.desc: The goddess that became Hades' wife in Greek mythology and who is said to have the power to bring fertility to the earth. While playing with the Oceanids, the earth cracked and Hades appeared and took her away to the underworld. Without her, the earth grew barren, but she was allowed to return by the other gods for several months of each year, bringing fertility back while she was free.

dvl.name: Orcus
dvl.desc: The god whose name was said to refer to the very underworld itself in Roman mythology. His huge and intimidating stature is often depicted in ancient Roman murals. However, he later was often associated with other Greek gods as time went on.

dvl.name: Chernobog
dvl.desc: The god of night, evil, and death, whose name means "black god" in Slavic lore. He is often depicted as the one who will destroy the world and is thought of more as a demon than a god. The curse, "May the black god kill you," is still used to this day.

dvl.name: Hel
dvl.desc:
The goddess of the underworld in Norse mythology. The word "Hell" was derived from her name. Her father is the god Loki and her mother is the giantess Angrboda. Her brothers are the giant wolf Fenrir and the world serpent Jormungandr.
Hel rules over Niflheim, the realm of the dead, where she controls the fate of all the souls of the dead. She is also the only known god in Norse mythology to have the power to bring the dead back to life.

dvl.name: Masakado
dvl.desc:
Taira no Masakado. A legendary samurai of the mid-heian period.
After conquering Kanto, he declared himself the new emperor of Japan, but soon fell to Hidesato Fujiwara and Sadamori Taira. He was enshrined to quell his spirit, and later became known as the guardian deity of Kanto.

dvl.name: Guan Yu
dvl.desc:
Now revered as a war god, Guan Yu was a famed general during the period of the Three Kingdoms. 
He banded with his blood brothers Liu Bei and Zhang Fei to rise up against the Yellow Turban Rebellion. Later on when he was captured after Liu Bei’s defeat by Cao Cao, it is said that Guan Yu refused to join Cao Cao because of his loyalty to Liu Bei.

dvl.name: Man Eater
dvl.desc: A man-eating temptress, she was once a woman that seduced countless men and committed unspeakable acts while alive. Now, even as a zombie, she maintains her appearance, continues to seduce men and literally devours them.

dvl.name: Bodyconian
dvl.desc: Wearing a form-fitting one-piece dress, with her hair long and straight, she is the embodiment of fasion from Japan's economic bubble years in the late 80's and early 90's.
