This style was particularly common in Tokyo where girls could often be found waving "Juliana Fans" as they danced the nights away. This "bodycon" culture burst along with the bubble and lives on now only in this zombified form.

dvl.name: Bayonetta
dvl.desc: A witch possessing magical powers, Bayonetta was discovered sealed away in a coffin at the bottom of a lake 20 years ago. With almost no memories of her previous life, the one thing she remembers is her mission to exterminate the Angels. Currently working with undertaker-cum-informant Enzo, she hates cockroaches and cry babies. The name "Bayonetta" was given to her by Rodin, owner of "The Gates of Hell".

dvl.name: Bayonetta☆
dvl.desc: A witch possessing magical powers, Bayonetta was discovered sealed away in a coffin at the bottom of a lake 20 years ago. With almost no memories of her previous life, the one thing she remembers is her mission to exterminate the Angels. Currently working with undertaker-cum-informant Enzo, she hates cockroaches and cry babies. The name "Bayonetta" was given to her by Rodin, owner of "The Gates of Hell".

dvl.name: Jeanne
dvl.desc: Like Bayonetta, Jeanne is also an Umbra Witch and a survivor of the witch hunts that occurred 500 years ago. With abilities and skills similar to Bayonetta, she is adept at performing Wicked Weaves and summoning the Infernal Demon Gomorrah, making her a worthy rival.

dvl.name: Jeanne☆
dvl.desc: Like Bayonetta, Jeanne is also an Umbra Witch and a survivor of the witch hunts that occurred 500 years ago. With abilities and skills similar to Bayonetta, she is adept at performing Wicked Weaves and summoning the Infernal Demon Gomorrah, making her a worthy rival.

dvl.name: Beloved
dvl.desc: A powerful Angel, tasked with vanquishing the enemies of Paradiso. With its superior combat abilities and stopping power, it has faced off against Bayonetta many times in the past.

dvl.name: Ara Mitama
dvl.desc: One of the four great aspects of Shinto thought, it has the power to grant wildness and ferocity. It is said to aid in one's bravery, growth, and endeavors, though it can lead in a negative direction.

dvl.name: Saki Mitama
dvl.desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it brings great bounty from the hunt. It is said to aid in love, profit, and growth, and can create new paths.

dvl.name: Kusi Mitama
dvl.desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it uses its power to bring good omens. It is said to aid in one's wisdom, observation, and skill, and can mend fractured paths.

dvl.name: Nigi Mitama
dvl.desc: One of the four aspects of Shinto thought, it works gently to help maintain a calm mind. It is said to aid in one's relations and sociability, and can lead one in a positive direction.

dvl.name: Shiva
dvl.desc:
The Hindu creator and destroyer of the world. Along with Vishnu, Shiva is one of the most revered gods in the Hindu faith. There is a belief that he will destroy the world near its end, purifying it during its reconstruction. He uses his destructive force towards demons, and bestows blessings on to those who worship him. His weapon is a trident of light, and his third eye is said to be able to set the world ablaze.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Nekomata
dvl.desc:
A cat yokai in Japanese folklore. Long-lived cats are said to become these creatures that have mastered human speech. The powers of the Nekomata vary, some were even strong enough to turn into people or command the dead.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Abaddon
dvl.desc:
Lord of the abyss in the Book of Revelation, the source of evil and cause of plagues. He leads the seventh order of demons who appear at the sounding of the fifth trumpet on Judgement Day, when he will command a horde of locusts wreaking havoc and suffering. His name means "destroyer" and "endless pit" and even considered the abyss itself.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Dante
dvl.desc: The proprietor of Devil May Cry, and a Devil Hunter of legendary proportions. Dante is a half-human, half-demon hybrid, born to a human woman Eva and the demon who saved the human world, Sparda. He overcame battle after arduous battle in his past, and currently serves as a barrier to any attempt by demons to invade his world. Dante greets any and all challengers with a signature smile on his face. At the behest of a client, Dante jumps back into the fray against demonic forces.

dvl.name: Dante☆
dvl.desc: The proprietor of Devil May Cry, and a Devil Hunter of legendary proportions. Dante is a half-human, half-demon hybrid, born to a human woman Eva and the demon who saved the human world, Sparda. He overcame battle after arduous battle in his past, and currently serves as a barrier to any attempt by demons to invade his world. Dante greets any and all challengers with a signature smile on his face. At the behest of a client, Dante jumps back into the fray against demonic forces.

dvl.name: Nero
dvl.desc:
The young Devil Hunter operating out of the mobile Devil May Cry.
Having lost his demonic arm (the Devil Bringer) before the events of the game,
he stands against the invading demonic forces with a new power provided by Nico.

dvl.name: Nero☆
dvl.desc:
The young Devil Hunter operating out of the mobile Devil May Cry.
Having lost his demonic arm (the Devil Bringer) before the events of the game,
he stands against the invading demonic forces with a new power provided by Nico.

dvl.name: V
dvl.desc: Book and cane in hand, this slender man appears covered in impressive tattoos. Before chaos fell upon Red Grave City, he sought out Dante through the information broker Morrison and tasked him to subdue a certain demon. V lacks the power to fight himself, instead relying on three demon familiars to take the offensive in battle.

dvl.name: V☆
dvl.desc: Book and cane in hand, this slender man appears covered in impressive tattoos. Before chaos fell upon Red Grave City, he sought out Dante through the information broker Morrison and tasked him to subdue a certain demon. V lacks the power to fight himself, instead relying on three demon familiars to take the offensive in battle.

dvl.name: Gogmagog
dvl.desc:
A giant said to have lived in ancient Britain.
He was so huge, he could destroy a ship with a single swing of his arm. He defended the island against intruders until he was defeated by the Trojan Brutus.

dvl.name: Tlaltecuhtli
dvl.desc:
A monster of Aztec lore.
During the earth's creation, she was ripped in half by Quetzalcoatl and Tezcatlipoca. Half became the earth and half became the sky.

dvl.name: Titan
dvl.desc: One of the three groups of children born from Gaia and Uranus in Greek lore. The Titans, unlike the other two groups, were born into human form. It is said they all wore bronze armor. They fought against the Olympians in Titanomachy, a great war that lasted 10 years, but were finally defeated.

dvl.name: Kwancha
dvl.desc:
A demon of disease that lives in the underworld of Nepali folklore.
A bringer of stomachaches, it will appear at crossroads. But if you make an offering and chant a mantra, it will defend you from sickness. He is also Shiva and Kali's attendant. There is a Nepali festival where Kwancha appears among other gods.

dvl.name: Hua Po
dvl.desc:
A tree spirit of Chinese lore who sprouts from trees used for hangings.
She is much smaller than a human, and cannot speak, but her voice is said to be as clear as a bird's song.

dvl.name: Kodama
dvl.desc:
A botanic spirit from Japanese folklore. They are said to have sprung from trees that are over a hundred years old.
They are the embodiment of the worshipping of trees, which can be found all over Japan and around the world.

dvl.name: Koropokkur
dvl.desc: Koropokkuru are a race of small people in Ainu folklore. They are considered to be folk that live under the butterbur plant, and is said to be benign and gentle. They used to live in harmony with the Ainu, but an incident caused them to avoid human contact.

dvl.name: Indrajit
dvl.desc: Indrajit is depicted as the son of Ravana, the great king of the Rakshasa, in the Sanskrit epics of ancient India, Ramayana. Originally named Meghanada, the god Brahma was so impressed with him for conquering Indra, gave him the name Indrajit. Meghanada means "Thunderous" or "Lord of Sky (Clouds)" and in fact it is said that he was truly worth of that name on the battlefield.

dvl.name: Yama
dvl.desc: The god in charge of hell in Hindu lore, also known as King Enma in Buddhism. He is believed to be the first human, and after his death was given the role of guiding the deceased to the land of the dead. He eventually began punishing the dead according to their deeds in life. Through Yama's work, hell was born over time and he became its master.

dvl.name: Asura
dvl.desc:
A ferocious type of demon in Hindu lore. Even the gods are troubled by these wrathful beings with immense strength and magical powers. They are very strict in their ways, and will relentlessly attack any wrongdoers to enforce their justice.
They were worshipped in Persia as the god of light and the chief god in Zoroastrianism, Ahura Mazda is said to be one of them.

dvl.name: Agni
dvl.desc: The god of fire in Hindu lore and also Buddhism. One of the most important gods depicted in the Rigveda, the collection of Vedic Sanskrit hymns originating in ancient India. He is the embodiment of fire, said to carry offerings to the gods through smoke, give testimony and even become the witness to weddings. He is the intermediary between the realm of the gods and human world.

dvl.name: Mahakala
dvl.desc: Indian god who repels evil, known as Daikokuten in Buddhism. His many swords are fearsome, but by paying tribute, the devout may be blessed with tremendous wealth and happiness. There are beliefs that Mahakala is actually just another name for Shiva the destroyer, or that he is the form Shiva takes when enraged.

dvl.name: Kartikeya
dvl.desc: A Hindu god of war and son of Shiva, also known as Skanda and Murugan. He rides upon a peacock called Paravani and is often depicted with 6 heads and 12 arms. He commands the army of the gods, and defeated the forces of Asura.

dvl.name: Gabriel
dvl.desc: One of the four major archangels in the angel hierarchy. The angel who gave the Annunciation to the Blessed Virgin Mary, Gabriel's name comes from the Sumerian word for "governor". Though most angels are depicted as being androgynous, Gabriel is sometimes considered to be female, due to depictions of her with features resembling those of a young girl.

dvl.name: Raphael
dvl.desc:
One of the four major archangels in the angel hierarchy. His name means "healer".
He is said to be the guardian of the Tree of Life that stands at the center of the Garden of Eden.

dvl.name: Uriel
dvl.desc: One of the four major archangels in the angel hierarchy. His name means "Flame of God",  and he is in charge of all celestial phenomena. On Judgment Day, he will pass judgement on the sins of the living and the dead.

dvl.name: Fafnir
dvl.desc: An evil dragon of Norse lore who was defeated by the hero Siegfried. In the Volsunga Saga, written around the  13th century, he is depicted as a giant wyrm with legs that shook the earth as he moved and could even spit poison.

dvl.name: Vasuki
dvl.desc: A giant serpent of Hindu legend. It is said the gods bound him to Mount Mandar to churn the sea of milk to create Amrita, the nectar of immortality. With the gods pulling him from one side and the Asura from the other, the strain caused him to vomit up potent venom. Shiva acted quickly to drink the venom before it could sour the Amrita.

dvl.name: Nidhoggr
dvl.desc: An evil dragon of Norse lore that dwells beneath Yggdrasil, gnawing at its roots for sustenance. He is known for leading his kin into war against Hraesvelgr. Even after Ragnarok the end of days, he will linger, feeding off the corpses of the dead.

dvl.name: Tiamat
dvl.desc: The primordial goddess of Babylonian lore whose form resembles a dragon. She governs the sea and gave birth to many deities with her consort Apsu, the god of fresh water. When war broke out between her and the gods, she spawned 11 monsters to fight by her side, but they were defeated by the leader of the gods, Marduk. Her body was first ripped apart and then used to create the world.

dvl.name: Ym
dvl.desc: A dragon of ancient Semitic lore of the Palestinian region. He is enemies with Baal, the god of fertility and agriculture. He dwells underwater and gains his powers by ruling the seas and rivers, which he also causes to flood. Even though it was Baal who defeated him, because there are similarities to the way Tiamat was killed by Marduk in Babylonian lore, some believe that Ym and Tiamat are in fact the same being.

dvl.name: Susano-o
dvl.desc:
A violent god of Japanese legend. Born to Izanagi and Izanami and brother of Amaterasu. Banned from Takaamagahara for uncouth behavior, he later performed heroic deeds such as slaying Orochi saving Kushinada who he then married. Soon after, he honors his sister with a godly gift, the sword of Kusanagi which he obtained from the tail of the Orochi.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Black Maria
dvl.desc:
A holy mother of the dark, of Christian descent.
The statues in regular churches are usually of the Virgin Mary, but some suspicious black statues do exist. They say that these statues have their origins in the Middle East, such as Egypt's Isis and the Phrygian Cybele.

dvl.name: Red Rider
dvl.desc:
One of the four horsemen of the apocalypse. He rides on a red horse and holds a great sword. He has the power to corrupt peace on earth and make people kill each other.
The four horsemen have the power to conquer and kill and often thought to bring chaos.

dvl.name: Black Rider
dvl.desc:
One of the four horsemen of the Apocalypse, he rides a black horse and carries a scale. He has the power to bring famine, and the right to end people's lives through their suffering. 
The four horsemen have the power to conquer and kill and often thought to bring chaos.

dvl.name: Pale Rider
dvl.desc:
One of the Four Horseman of the Apocalypse, he rides a pale horse and represents death. He has the power to destroy life.
The four horsemen have the power to conquer and kill and often thought to bring chaos.

dvl.name: Neko Shogun
dvl.desc: A prophetic taoist god with the body of a human and the head of a cat. Originally known as Mao Shogun, he was a general around the 14th to 15th century. His tomb is said to be located in Annam, now known as Vietnam. Because his name was phonetically identical to the word "Cat" in his native tongue, he was reborn as the new god Neko Shogun. ("Neko" means "Cat" in Japanese.)

dvl.name: Frost Ace
dvl.desc:
A Jack Frost who donned an Ice Vest and turned into a superhero.
Little is known about him, but rumor has it there was a tragic incident and now his heart burns with vengeance, though it is still frozen in sorrow. As Fate toys with this dark hero, what will he do? Will he exact vengeance, or be a merciful hero? Hiding his insecurities behind that cool and cute face, he continues to fight on.

dvl.name: Garuda
dvl.desc:
A gargantuan bird in Indian lore, greatest enemy of the Naga. To save his captured mother from the Naga, He stole Amrita from the gods in exchange for her freedom. Impressed, Vishnu grants Garuda immortality in exchange for becoming his steed.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Masakado
dvl.desc:
Taira no Masakado. A legendary samurai of the mid-heian period.
After conquering Kanto, he declared himself the new emperor of Japan, but soon fell to Hidesato Fujiwara and Sadamori Taira. He was enshrined to quell his spirit, and later became known as the guardian deity of Kanto.
Moved by the Liberators' determination to protect Tokyo, he regained his original form and power to give them aid.

dvl.name: Asura Lord
dvl.desc:
The king of the Asuras, which are a ferocious race of demons in Hindu lore. Even the gods are troubled by these wrathful beings with immense strength and magical powers. They are very strict in their ways, and will relentlessly attack any wrongdoers to enforce their justice. 
Vairocana, a king of the Asuras is said to be associated with the Zoroastrian god Ahura Mazda. In Buddhism, he is known as Dainichi Nyorai, the supreme Buddha.

dvl.name: Cu Chulainn
dvl.desc:
A gallant Celtic hero, son of the sun god Lugh. His weapon is the mighty spear Gae Bolg. His good looks could be deceiving, for in battle he is ferocious, tearing down his enemies and wiping out entire armies.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Quetzalcoatl
dvl.desc:
An Aztec creator god known as "the feathered serpent". He created humans from his own blood and known as the god of wind and giver of life. Quetzalcoatl is identified as the sun, and Venus is said to be his heart. Initially he was worshiped as the god of water and harvest, later recognized as the god of culture.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Vairocana
dvl.desc:
A king of the Asura in Hindu myth. Son of Prahlada and father of Bali. His name means "One Who Shines On All", and he is also known as Maha (Great) Vairocana. 
He was the enemy of Indra, the leader of the Devas, and was eventually vanquished by Indra.
In Buddhism he is known as Dainichi Nyorai, and is sometimes thought to be the universe itself.

dvl.name: Atavaka
dvl.desc: Among the eight Yashaou, he is the god of warfare and protection in Buddhist lore. Also called the Great General Myo-o. Originally a child-eating demon in Hindu mythology, he was incorporated into Buddhism and became a protector figure. It is said that when Siddhartha died, he imparted the teachings of Buddha to the gods and made them swear to protect humanity.

dvl.name: Hecate
dvl.desc: Her duty sees the dead and those who incur the wrath of gods suffer by her extremely cruel hands. She is master of the Furies, goddesses of revenge. Her name means "she who acts from afar," and is associated with the moon. Later, when she was turned into a demon, she began to be depicted as having three heads, a dog's, a lion's and a horse's.

dvl.name: Hresvelgr
dvl.desc:
A giant eagle in Norse mythology that sits at the very top of the world tree Yggdrasil. The winds blow whenever it beats its wings. 
It is forever at war with the snake Nidhoggr, which lives at the tree's roots.

dvl.name: Gurr
dvl.desc: A demon that takes the shape of a giant bird in Sri Lankan lore. It is thought to be a derivation of Garuda.

dvl.name: Anzu
dvl.desc: An evil deity of Mesopotamian folklore with an eagle's body and lion's head. While the god of Enlil purified himself, Anzu stole the Tablets of Destiny from him.

dvl.name: Moh Shuvuu
dvl.desc:
Meaning "evil bird," it's the ghost of a young girl who died without knowing love in Buryat lore.
She seduces travelers, only to crack their heads open and suck out their brains with her beak.

dvl.name: Camazotz
dvl.desc: An evil bat who dwelled in Xibalba in Mayan lore. When the heroic twins Xbalanque and Hunahpu went to Xibalba, he decapitated Hunahpu at the Bat House.

dvl.name: Lucifuge
dvl.desc:
Lucifuge Rofocale, whose name means "he who flees the light", is the prime minister of Hell, watching over the government. He is Demon Lord Lucifer's counterpart.
On his head are three twisting horns, and he has a goat's body with a long tail. Lucifer ordered him to manage the world's fortune, and he has Baal, Agares, and Marbas at his command. He is also an officer of contracts, granting his conjurers' wishes in exchange for their souls.

dvl.name: Tokisada
dvl.desc:
Fully known as Amakusa Shiro Tokisada, his baptismal name was "Geronimo", though it became "Francisco" during the time of the rebellion.
He was the leader of the Kan-ei 14 (1637) rebellion of Shimabara, though it is said that the mastermind behind the rebellion was someone else, and Shiro was only a figurehead. After successfully defeating the Shogunate army several times, the rebels were finally besieged at Hara Castle and killed. His head was put on public display. He lived a mere 16 years.

dvl.name: Guts
dvl.desc: The "Black Swordsman" is armed with a prosthetic hand and a huge sword called the "Dragon Slayer". His body is battered and bruised, but strong and tough as well, which helps him on his journey for revenge.

dvl.name: Schierke
dvl.desc: The dearest student of Flora the witch. A very talented apprentice witch, she is capable despite her young age, but can sometimes be a little too serious for her own good... Schierke is working with Guts on a mission assigned to her by her mistress.

dvl.name: Skull Knight
dvl.desc: An entity that exists between the Astral World and the Physical World. He appears before Guts from time to time. Sometimes to lend a hand in battle, sometimes to guide Guts with cryptic words.

dvl.name: Mozgus
dvl.desc: A Holy See inquisitor known by the alias "Bloody Scripture." His piety towards his faith is so strong that he has no mercy for heretics and sinners alike, and has dealt punishment to countless people in the past.

dvl.name: Anat
dvl.desc:
The goddess of birth and death in Semitic lore. She is Baal's sister and wife.
Like Baal, she is a god of fertility, but is also known for her terrible curse of death. It is said that even her father El in the heavens feared her power. She cast an annual curse of death on the ruler of the underworld and her son/son-in-law, Mot, which caused the cycle of fertility of the land. Fertilized by the blood of men, her altar was constantly supplied with human sacrifices.

dvl.name: Lakshmi
dvl.desc: The goddess of beauty and good fortune in Hindu lore. Vishnu's wife and Kama's mother, she is the goddess of love. She is the embodiment of beauty and is unrivaled. Lakshmi is a fabulous dancer, charming even the gods with her enchanting moves. A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Tzitzimitl
dvl.desc: Goddess of Aztec myth who governs night and fear. Her war with the sun god caused a catastrophic solar eclipse, making her a symbol of death and evil. She also demands a sacrifice every 52 years.

dvl.name: Alice
dvl.desc:
A ghost who appears as a small blonde girl. Contrary to how she looks, her magical powers are formidable. Some say she is the ghost of an English girl who suffered a gruesome death. Others claim she was born from the twisted desires of a disturbed writer's mind, alas not even she can recall the truth.
She fights the Liberators in a game of life and death within an underground maze.

dvl.name: Belial
dvl.desc:
One of the 72 demons of the Goetia, invoked by King Solomon. He leads 50 to 80 legions of demons as their chief.
He once was a seraphim who fell, and is said to appear before his conjurer as two beautiful angels in a chariot of fire and blesses them by granting them high social status. His name means "worthless" and he is cunning, causing the fall of Sodom and Gomorrah, as well as persecuting Jesus Christ.

dvl.name: Nebiros
dvl.desc:
The general of Hell. He keeps watch over other demons.
One of hell's greatest necromancers, he can control souls and corpses. He has the ability to discover the Hand of Glory, which is said to be made from the hand of one who was given the death penalty. He also has knowledge of ore, plants, and animals, and can foresee the future.

dvl.name: Kali
dvl.desc:
A goddess of Indian mythology. She is one of the consorts of Shiva, the god of destruction.
The name "Kali" means "black one" and is derived from the word "kala" (black), but has also come to mean "goddess of time."
She is usually depicted with four arms, each of which is always carrying a blood-stained weapon or a severed head.
Kali is identified with Durga, an alternate aspect of Parvati transformed by anger at Asura into a fearsome form.

dvl.name: Xi Wangmu
dvl.desc:
A goddess revered in ancient China who grew popular during the Han dynasty. Her palace is said to be atop the mythological Mt. Kunlun.
She is mostly human in appearance, with a distinctive headdress as well as the tail of a panther and the teeth of a tiger. Originally she was said to have governed the Five Calamities, but later came to be depicted as a beautiful sage and enshrined as the ruler of Mt. Kunlun. She is known for holding the secret of immortality, which was showcased in a famous episode where Sun Wukong stole and ate the Peaches of Immortality in her garden.

dvl.name: Demonee-Ho
dvl.desc: Jack Frost equipped with his own mini-armor. Rumor has it that he participates in operations all over the world, and has a legendary 100% mission completion rate. He originally donned the armor because he admired it, but after long, hard training, he emerged as the perfect soldier. He may look as cute as the loveable Jack Frost, but don't underestimate him because he'll make you stop crying or laughing.

dvl.name: Maya
dvl.desc: The Hindu personification of Illusion. It is said to have the power to make humans aware and become enlightened about "phenomena" caused by things on earth. An important element in the universe's structure, Maya has relations with the great goddess Kali, and is sometimes equated with the Buddha's mother Queen Maya, due to the Buddha being the one who awakens from the illusion that is Maya.

dvl.name: Norn
dvl.desc: Goddesses of fate in Norse lore. The three sisters are called, Urd who represents the "past", Verdandi the "present" and Skuld the "future". They live below the roots of Yggdrasil and weave the threads of fate, which even the gods are bound by.

dvl.name: Marici
dvl.desc: Known as Marishiten in Japan, she is a sun goddess of Buddhism. Her name means "light" or "heat haze". In Japan, she was worshiped by warriors, said to give the benefits of protection from harm and the ability to attack the enemy without being noticed. She is often portrayed as having 3 heads, 6 or 8 arms with weapons like swords, bows, and vajra.

dvl.name: Aniel
dvl.desc:
He is the angel of beauty. His name means "grace of God." He is generally associated with the planet Venus and performs a similar role as the goddess Ishtar.
He gives rise to feelings of love amongst people and has the role of tying together young men and women.
He is the leader of the Virtues and Principalities, and rules over Scorpio and Pisces of the zodiac.
He is also said to be one of the angels who bore the prophet Enoch to heaven.

dvl.name: Clotho
dvl.desc:
One of the three Moirae Sisters in Greek lore.
She spins the threads of fate.
It is said that one's fate is determined by the color and thickness of this thread, and that she is the one who decides a person's birth.
She also deceived Typhon into eating the ephemeral fruit on Nysa to help the gods to secure their victory.

dvl.name: Lachesis
dvl.desc:
One of the three Moirae Sisters in Greek lore.
She is the apportioner, measuring the thread which determines each person's lifespan with a rod.
She is said to have participated in the Titanomachy, helping the gods by killing the giants Agrius and Thoas with bronze clubs.

dvl.name: Atropos
dvl.desc:
One of the three Moirae Sisters in Greek lore.
She cuts the life threads of those whose time has come according to the measurements made by Lachesis with her shears.
She is the "unturnable", for it is she who determines a person's death.
The three Moirae Sisters appear in the forms of the Mother, the Virgin and the Hag, representing "the Past, the Present and the Future" or" Birth, Life and Death."

dvl.name: Azazel
dvl.desc: A leader of the Grigori, angels that descended to earth to watch over mankind. They lusted after beautiful human women, making them their wives, and taught the humans forbidden knowledge, angering God. Azazel had knowledge of weapons and cosmetics. Men soon learned how to fight, and women learned to be promiscuous.

dvl.name: Tachikoma
dvl.desc:
A type of small, multiped think tank used by Public Security Section 9. Capable of operating independently due to its advanced AI.
Standard loadout includes a chain gun, grenade launcher and other firearms, as well as thermoptic camouflage and a driver's pod at the rear.
Tachikoma is able to support Kusanagi and her team in all types of tactical situations.

dvl.name: Motoko Kusanagi
dvl.desc:
A full-prosthetic cyborg whose body is fully mechanical except for her brain and parts of her spinal cord.
An outstanding commander with exceptional leadership and combat skills, she is also a Wizard Class hacker.
Kusanagi is the leader of a small elite special forces law enforcement team called Public Security Section 9. Her teammates address her by the rank of Major.

dvl.name: Lilith
dvl.desc:
Adam's first wife in the Old Testament. She became a demon after leaving Eden. There are various theories as to how she fell, but all agree she is an iconic adulteress. When she rebelled against God, she was cursed to have a snake's tail instead of legs, and often depicted as such.
She emerged from the Summoning Portal at the Liberators' Tokyo Branch one day to test the potential of human desire. Her power proved too great for mortals to handle.

dvl.name: Flauros
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. He appears as a leopard and can see the past and future. He can control fire and burn all his adversaries to death.

dvl.name: Ardha
dvl.desc: Ardhanarishvara is a god of dual gender whose appearance is half that of the destroyer, Shiva, and half his wife, Parvati. Ardha is the ideal figure of Shaktism, the perfect god. Ardha is often depicted with the iconography of both Shiva (trident, tiger skin and bull mount Nandi) and Parvati (lotus, ornaments and lion) combined.

dvl.name: Angra Mainyu
dvl.desc: A deity symbolizing evil in the dualistic cosmology of Zoroastrianism. On meeting his counterpart Spenta Mainyu, Angra Mainyu chose Evil out of the two principles of Good and Evil. Angra Mainyu went on to create scourges like winter, sickness and vice, as well as harmful creatures like Azi Dahaka. It is said that he fell into darkness but returned to fight Ahura Mazda again.

dvl.name: Demiurge
dvl.desc:
An imperfect god of Gnosticism who created the material world.
According to Gnostics of the Roman Empire, the Demiurge proclaims himself as God; when Adam and Eve gain "knowledge," he cast them out in anger. The Demiurge wishes for the souls of humans to be trapped in the material world forever.

dvl.name: Berserker
dvl.desc: Guts equipped with the dwarf-made enchanted item, the Berserker Armor. When aligned with the diabolical Od dwelling within it, the armor's wearer is driven by such violent emotions that they become oblivious to pain and fear,  fighting with a demonic prowess that exceeds the limits of the human body like a true Berserker. When consumed by the armor, the wearer will attack anything in sight with no distinction between friend and foe. Continued use of the armor will ultimately result in the wearer losing their sensibility to light, sounds and warmth amongst other things.

dvl.name: Zodd
dvl.desc: An Apostle who has had a complicated history with Guts. Feared as "Nosferatu Zodd" on the battlefield, he holds power as the highest virtue, pledging his allegiance to Griffith after being defeated by him.

dvl.name: Griffith
dvl.desc: Leader of the Band of the Hawk, Griffith is a young man of extraordinary beauty. He was Guts' greatest friend and rival, but now he is Guts' nemesis and object of hate.

dvl.name: Ose Hallel
dvl.desc:
Ose, who was once one of the Fallen, with his angelic power restored by God.
He is ranked as one of the Seraph, a type of angel placed as the highest in the nine ranks of the angel hierarchy by Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite.
The fallen angel Ose is said to have the ability to make people believe that they are the king or pope, but only for an hour a day.
One theory is that Ose is the corrupt form of Odin after being incorporated into Christianity.

dvl.name: Flauros Hallel
dvl.desc:
Flauros, who was once one of the Fallen, with his angelic power restored by God.
He is ranked as one of the Seraph, who in Paradise Lost by John Milton were considered as equals to the four Archangels.
The fallen angel Flauros is listed as the sixty-fourth spirit and is a Great Duke of Hell with 36 legions of demons under his command. It is said that within the magic triangle from which he is summoned he will gladly tell the tale of how the angels fell, and will even protect his summoner from the temptations of other demons if ordered to do so.

dvl.name: Master Therion
dvl.desc:
The name of the beast that the mystic Aleister Crowley called himself. It refers to the beast that appears in the Book of Revelations.
According to Revelations, Therion is the enemy of humanity, a beast with the power and authority of Satan. The beast is said to come from the sea, having seven heads and ten horns, a body like a leopard and rugged legs like a bear. Another beast with lamb's horns is said to come from the earth and force man into worshipping the beast from the sea. Everyone must also bear the name, number or mark of the beast to buy or sell anything.
This number, 666, in turn became known as the "number of the beast".

dvl.name: Sraosha
dvl.desc:
In Zoroastrian lore, Sraosha's duty is to listen to humanity's cries and relay them to Ahura Mazda. His name literally means 'observance'.
He is tasked with watching over the souls of the dead and guides them to where they are to be judged, while warding off any hostile demons.
Even after sunset when his powers wan, he has been known to descend to do battle against Aeshma and protect humanity against its rage and violence.

dvl.name: Thor
dvl.desc:
The Norse god of thunder. Later known as the god of agriculture, he was worshipped mostly by farmers.
Thor is a heroic and honest god with unrivaled strength. Some claim he could even swallow a cow whole.
With the magical hammer Mjolnir which returns to its owner after being thrown, he smites his enemies with ease.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Surt
dvl.desc: A fire giant in Norse lore. He rules the fire realm, Muspelheim, and brandishes the burning sword Laevateinn. At Ragnarok, he will set the world ablaze. A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Mahamayuri
dvl.desc: Known as Kujaku Myo-o in Japan, he is known to remove misfortune, fear, and poison. This is due to the fact that he is the deification of the peacock, which eats poisonous snakes. He is often portrayed as riding a peacock, holding a lotus or peacock feather, and has a graceful expression, unlike the other Wisdom Kings that are depicted in more wrathful fashion. In Shingon Buddhism, founded by the monk Kukai, it is said he is an incarnation of Buddha, taking that form to enlighten people.

dvl.name: Cernunnos
dvl.desc: A beast god of Celtic lore, worshiped by Druids. He has deer antlers and is usually pictured with horned snakes. He is the god of the dead, hunting, fertility, and vegetation. He is thought to be the lord of the underworld, or rather the realm after life, and the keeper that guards the gate between life and death. While being a god of fertility, his purpose is to actually harvest the souls of the dead and ferry them to their next lives, so he is believed to be a grim reaper of sorts as well.

dvl.name: Pales
dvl.desc: A god or goddess with a donkey's head who was worshiped from northern Africa all the way to Rome. The donkey's head has long been a sign of fertility and is often worshiped. His or her (there is some dispute amongst scholars) temple was built on Palatine Hill in Rome. The word "palace" came from this god's name.

dvl.name: Mandrake
dvl.desc: A magical plant whose roots look like a human. There are male and female versions. Mandrakes are a precious component in potions to heal sickness, but obtaining one is very hard. When pulled from the ground, they give a bloodcurdling scream, killing anyone unlucky enough to hear it.

dvl.name: Alraune
dvl.desc: A cursed wood spirit in the form of a beautiful woman that's known to bloom under the gallows when innocents condemned to death shed their last tears or as the dead ejaculate when their necks snap. Her flowers take the shape of purple bells, which bears an orange fruit, and its roots take on a humanoid appearance. This puts her into the same family as the Mandrake and her fruits are used to produce drugs or hypnotics, while some even believe them to be a kind of panacea. Like the Mandrake, she's also known for letting out a bloodcurdling scream when pulled from the ground, but humans throughout history have sought after her despite any such dangers. Originally appearing in German legends as an evil female spirit, her name can also be interpreted as the "teller of secrets".

dvl.name: Es
dvl.desc: Instinctual desires buried deep within the human psyche. The famed Austrian psychologist, Freud, described this as one of the three agents, the id, that encompass human mentality. Es embodies this instinctual, uncoordinated energy that drives our subconscious minds towards attaining pleasure and fulfilling our own selfish needs. In reality, humans are grounded by social niceties with the ego acting as the mediator between the id and any such rules or constructs. Nonetheless, Es will attempt to draw our carnal desires to the surface, while a mind's super-ego works to counter this.

dvl.name: Erlkonig
dvl.desc: An evil wood spirit appearing in Germany's Scharzwald. He charms people and leads them to their deaths. His name means "Alder King", and true to his name, he is the ruler of the alders of the Black Forest. Alder trees tend to begin life in places with damp soil, but can grow in even the most barren environments. It is said that the Erlkonig is the strongest of the alder trees. Humans who encroached upon his forest were cleverly charmed and led to their deaths, which gave rise to tales of a demonic tree brimming with evil.

dvl.name: Sonic
dvl.desc:
The Supersonic Hedgehog that wants to maintain his title of being the fastest ever.
He enjoys his freedom and hates twists and turns. Although he's a a bit shortsighted, he has the heart to help out those in need.
He believes that life is a series of adventures and mishaps, while even finding excitement in the world being in peril since that's exactly what he wants to experience. He the Hedgehog that's "kind of a big deal" and can't stay still. He's Sonic the Hedgehog.

dvl.name: Vouivre
dvl.desc: Vouivre can be traced back to the Latin word for "viper". Sometimes depicted as a beautiful female spirit. They have bat wings, eagle legs, a snake tail and are all female. The secret of their power is the garnet gem in their forehead. If it is stolen, they lose their power and must obey the gem's owner.

dvl.name: Beelzebub (Human)
dvl.desc: The King of Hell, known as "Lord of the Flies." By making them carry the souls of the dead, he keeps the flies he rules in order. In the Bible he is mentioned as one of the most formidable demons of high rank. It is also said that he was once the lord Baal of Canaan who was punished and became Beelzebub. Despite his power, Beelzebub's power was long sealed away by forcing a part of him to take on a human form, but was reinvigorated by the Aura Gate as he sought to reclaim his station.

dvl.name: Beelzebub
dvl.desc: The King of Hell, known as "Lord of the Flies." By making them carry the souls of the dead, he keeps the flies he rules in order. In the Bible he is mentioned as one of the most formidable demons of high rank. It is also said that he was once the lord Baal of Canaan who was punished and became Beelzebub. In rebellion, his enemies plotted to seal away his powers and were successful by forcing a part of him to take on a human form, but was able to return to his former glory by being fused back together. With his long lost powers at hand, he now seeks to reclaim his throne.

dvl.name: Gemori
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia, and the only female among them. She is a beautiful woman with a golden crown and pure white lace. Also known as the Duchess of Poetry. She is said to have the power to see the past and future, knows how to gain the love of women, and sometimes turns into an ugly woman to test her summoners.

dvl.name: Murmur
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia, he is called the Great Duke of Thrones. He appears clad in blue armor, riding a gryphon, and wearing a crown that signifies his status as a Duke. Philosophy and necromancy (commanding the spirits of the dead in particular) are his forte, and he can use any corpse as a vengeful spirit. He also leads over 30 armies as a Grand Duke of Hell.

dvl.name: Koga Saburo
dvl.desc: Koga Saburo. A legendary figure from the story Suwa Engi of the Shintoshu, a collection of stories of gods. He wandered into the underworld and eventually made it back to the surface, becoming a snake in the process. He was eventually worshipped at Suwa Shrine as Suwa Daimyojin. This story is believed to be a variation on Take-Minakata of Japanese lore. In that version, as Take-Minakata, he subjugates Mishaguji, but then is defeated by Take-Mikazuchi. He flees overseas, where he transforms into the snake god there before finding his way back to Suwa.

dvl.name: Batou
dvl.desc:
A nearly full-prosthetic cyborg with special enhancements. Not only is he a great fighter and marksman, he's also a talented hacker who has effectively become Motoko Kusanagi's right hand man in Section 9.
He was formerly a Ranger serving under the JGSDF and it was there that he was outfitted with his "sleepless" cybernetic eyes.
An imposing figure with an outgoing personality, he's also very amicable and is the Tachikomas' favorite member of Section 9.

dvl.name: Baldur
dvl.desc:
The god of light in Norse lore and son of Odin and Frigg. He is married to Nanna and has two brothers, Hod and Hermod, and a son named Forseti.
He was loved by all the gods, but after having a nightmare of his death, Frigg made all the plants and animals swear not to harm Baldur. Only the mistletoe was passed over as it was too young. Hearing this, Loki tricked Hod into shooting a mistletoe at Baldur, which killed him.
Hel promised to revive Baldur if every living thing cried for him, but the giantess Thokk refused to weep. When it was found that Thokk was Loki in disguise, the gods punished him.
With the world's light gone due to the death of Baldur, it took its first steps toward Ragnarok.

dvl.name: David
dvl.desc: A violinist of inhuman power who appears as a skeleton. He travels around Europe with wandering minstrels and plays his enchanting violin that causes people to dance the dance of death by bringing them to a state of bewilderment.

dvl.name: Elizabeth
dvl.desc:
The third princess in line to the throne of the Kingdom of Liones, and a waitress at the Boar Hat.
She is also the reincarnation of the Goddess Elizabeth, the daughter of the Supreme Deity.
She is destined to fall in love with Meliodas once they meet, but is inflicted with the Demon King's Perpetual Reincarnation curse that causes her to die in front of Meliodas three days after regaining her past memories.

dvl.name: Ban
dvl.desc:
〈The Fox Sin of Greed〉 of 〈The Seven Deadly Sins〉
He attained immortality by drinking from the Fountain of Youth in the Fairy King's Forest.
He is also prepared to do whatever he must to resurrect the love of his life, Elaine.

dvl.name: Meliodas
dvl.desc:
The son of the King of the Demon Clan. 
Before his emotions were removed from him, Meliodas was the captain of 〈The Seven Deadly Sins〉 as  〈The Dragon Sin of Wrath〉, as well as the owner of the Boar Hat.
3,000 years ago, he met and fell in love with Elizabeth, while betraying the Demon Clan in the process.
For this, the Supreme Deity cursed him with Immortality, but his journey continues as he searches for a way to break the curses that were placed on both him and Elizabeth.

dvl.name: Ladon
dvl.desc: A giant hundred-headed dragon from Greek mythology. It was born from Echidna and Typhon where each of its heads is of a different color and is said to be able to talk. It sleeplessly guards the Golden Apple at Hesperides, which were a wedding gift to Zeus and Hera from Gaia. According to certain accounts, Ladon was killed by Heracles in order to steal the Golden Apples it was guarding by using an arrow soaked with the poisonous blood of a Hydra. It is also said that following its death, Ladon was raised to the heavens by Hera and became the constellation Draco.

dvl.name: Echidna
dvl.desc: A monster from Greek mythology. Her upper half is a beautiful woman while her lower half is a spotted snake, and her name means "She-Viper". She gave birth to the most number of monstrous offspring in Greek mythology, including Cerberus, Orthrus, Hydra, Chimera and Ladon. She used her human half to lure unsuspecting travelers to her and devour them soon after. She was considered immortal according to some, but others also said that she was killed at the hands of the hundred-eyed giant, Argus.

dvl.name: Futsunushi
dvl.desc: The Nihonshoki sword deity whose name comes from "futsu," the fashion in which things are cut, and "nushi," his nature as a god. As such, it is said that he embodies the power that is bestowed upon swords. According to the Nihonshoki, when Izanagi used the Sword of Totsuka to angrily kill Kagutsuchi, the blood that dripped from this blade became the stones from which Futsunushi would be born. It is also said that Takamimusbi sent Futsunushi to pacify Ashihara-no-Nakatsukuni.

dvl.name: Adramelech
dvl.desc: The Chancellor of Hell, supervisor of Lucifer's wardrobe and even the President of the Senate of demons. He has the body of a mule and the plumage of a peacock. He was worshipped by the Assyrians, who sometimes offered children to him as a sacrifice.

dvl.name: Cerberus
dvl.desc: A large three-headed beast from Greek mythology, guard dog of the gateway to the underworld and often depicted with a snake for a tail. Born to the giant of wind Typhon and the snake Echidna, its brother is Orthrus. A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Maria
dvl.desc: The maternal figure of Christianity. Gabriel informed her that she was to be the mother of Jesus, and gave birth to him in the land of Bethlehem. Originally human, some sects revere her as the Virgin Mary for giving birth to the Son of God. Following the death of Jesus, the course of her earthly life was deemed complete where she would then be assumed body and soul into heavenly glory. It is even said that Gabriel bestowed upon her a white lily when she conceived her son in recognition of her purity.

dvl.name: Astaroth
dvl.desc: One of the 72 demons of the Goetia. A beautiful fallen angel said to be a duke of Hell. He appears in the form of a prince riding a dragon and leads an army of 40 evil spirits, and it is also said that he can see both the past as well as the future. Originally he was the goddess Astarte in Phoenicia, or modern-day Syria, but became warped into his current form by the Judeo-Christian God. In Christianity, he is a fallen angel that lures men into leading indolent lives.

dvl.name: Arioch
dvl.desc: The fallen angel of Israel and the demon of vengeance. His name means "ferocious lion" and he is said to aid in vengeance of those who seek his service. During his time as an angel of God, he was recognized as the guardian angel of the saint Enoch. It is said that his name originally belonged to one in either the Book of Genesis or the Book of Daniel from the Old Testament, only to become associated with the demon thereafter.

dvl.name: Nyarlathotep
dvl.desc: A god of the Cthulhu mythos. He came to Earth in ancient times from outer space and is known as the Crawling Chaos. He acts as a proxy to his masters such as Azathoth, who have no intelligence to make their desires manifest in our world. Because he can assume various forms, he is known as a faceless god. He is particularly known as the Haunter of the Dark, and he seems to have other guises on Earth as well.

dvl.name: Mada
dvl.desc: A giant Hindu monster whose name means "He who Intoxicates". It was created by the sage Chyavana out of fire and it is also said that it can swallow its enemies whole. Some say that not even Indra could stand up to its might.

dvl.name: Tezcatlipoca
dvl.desc:
A fearsome creator god of Aztec lore. His name means "smoking mirror."
A god of many things, including war, he was the first sun god before he was struck down by Quetzalcoatl. Some even consider him truly omnipotent due to his ability to freely give and take life as he wishes.

dvl.name: Cthulhu
dvl.desc: The original ruler of Earth who arrived on this planet several hundred million years ago according to H. P. Lovecraft's "Cthulhu Mythos". This gargantuan monster stands several hundred meters in height, has a scaly, rubbery-looking body, possesses an octopus-like head, a face covered in feelers, wings like a bat, as well as hands and feet with massive claws. It is even said that Cthulhu's voice resonates like an unholy oboe and is so disturbing that humans who hear it ultimately losing their minds. It slumbers beneath the Pacific Ocean within the sunken city of R'lyeh as it awaits its revival.

dvl.name: Vritra
dvl.desc: A giant, vicious dragon of Indian myth. Its name means "obstacle," for it blocks rainfall from the heavens. Indra returned the rain by defeating it, but the dragon always resurrects and the battle begins anew. The struggle between the two is an endless cycle.

dvl.name: Vishnu
dvl.desc: One of the primary gods in the Hindu lore. He is called "the preserver" and the incarnation of sun light. Appearing in different locations in one of his ten "Avatar" forms, he saves the world from danger and restores peace. A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Ame no Uzume
dvl.desc: The goddess of entertainment in Japanese lore. She governs many sacred dances and is most famous for the provocative dance she used to lure out Amaterasu, who had barricaded herself inside a cave. She later became Sarutahiko's wife.

dvl.name: Lanling Wang
dvl.desc: Also known as Raryou-oh, a general of the Northern Qi who wore a mask during battles to hide his beauty. During the 600s, he became famous for leading the battle against the neighboring Northern Zhou. It is even said that he led a battalion of 500 cavalrymen into battle while wearing an ugly mask because his face was too beautiful for the battlefield. His deeds later became the central subject of a Chinese opera that eventually made its way over to Japan and into the Japanese imperial court as a piece of Gagaku music of the Togaku form. In this adaptation, Lanling Wang dons a terrifying dragon mask.

dvl.name: Samyaza
dvl.desc: A fallen angel found in the Book of Enoch, where he gave humans knowledge of God. The Grigori, a group of angels which descended upon the earth to watch humans, instead began to lust for women. Because of that, God marked them with the stigma of fallen angels. They also taught humans warfare, which angered God and caused him to send the Great Flood. Samyaza is a leader of the Grigori. He is even believed to be the father of all magicians.

dvl.name: Heimdall
dvl.desc: He is one of the most beautiful gods of Norse lore and is also known as the White God. He guards the Bifrost Bridge, the entrance to the land of the gods, Asgard, and will blow his Gjallarhorn to signal the beginning of the end of all nine worlds. He and Loki are fated to kill each other at the end of Ragnarok.

dvl.name: Fariedone
dvl.desc: The mythical hero of Persian lore who defeated the evil Azhi Dahaka. It is said that he could even repel plague and other diseases. By felling the three-headed dragon that was terrorizing his people, Azhi Dahaka, he was able to restore the Persian crown to its former glory. However, he did not kill Azhi Dahaka after he noticed that serpents, scorpions and other foul creatures would spew forth each time he stabbed it with his sword. Thus, he imprisoned Azhi Dahaka under Mount Damavand instead of killing it.

dvl.name: Elohim
dvl.desc: A name that appears often in the Old Testament and is referred to as God in the Hebrew Bible. In ancient Semitic lore, it is referred to as "El" in a singular manner but also as pantheon of gods at times. Many theories pertaining to the true identity of this being exist but most seem to agree that it is a single deity, the God of Israel.

dvl.name: Anahita
dvl.desc: A Zoroastrian goddess whose name means "pure." While primarily known as a beautiful deity who rules over rivers and water, she is also the goddess of health, fertility, safe delivery, production of livestock, harvest, wealth and expansion of land. She is often portrayed as an elegant virgin wearing a crown decorated with numerous stars in addition to a golden necklace and a golden cape, and is typically shown holding a water jug. She is also a brave god of war astride a four-wheeled chariot, toppling demons and tyrants alike. Both her allies and her enemies have been said to have offered their prayers to her.

dvl.name: Shaddai
dvl.desc: One of the names for God that appears within the Old Testament. While its original meaning is unclear, it is most commonly translated into English as God Almighty. In the Book of Genesis, Abraham, the father of the Israelites, is said to have sworn himself to Shaddai in exchange for his descendants being given the land of Canaan. Based on the Kabbalah school of thought from Jewish mysticism, this name can also be interpreted as referring to Yesode, one of the ten sephirah.

dvl.name: Chi You
dvl.desc: A deity from Chinese mythology who is said to be descended from Shennong, the emperor of fire and agriculture, as well as one of the Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors. In ancient China, he sought control of Huang Di's throne and fought against him alongside his brothers. However, Huang Di would ultimately defeat, shackle and kill Chi You. Chinese historical records refer to Chi You as a god of war who invented five different weapons and wielded them in battle.

dvl.name: Sabaoth
dvl.desc: One of the names for God that appears within the Old Testament. It seems to reference armies or hosts. In the Book of Samuel, it is depicted as an almighty being that would lead the Israelites to victory by coming to their aid and vanquishing their foes. Based on the Kabbalah school of thought from Jewish mysticism, the seventh sephirah, Netzach, can be interpreted as being Netzach Sabaoth, while the eighth, Hod, can be interpreted as being Elohim Sabaoth.

dvl.name: Sukuna-Hikona
dvl.desc: One of the gods of Japanese lore, who is also known as Sukuna-Hikona-no-Mikoto. Older tales speak of him as the son of Kamimusubi, but is the son of Takamimusubi according to the Nihonshoki. He was apparently so small that he fell through his parents' fingers at birth. Though he would normally be counted among the Amatsukami, he became blood-brothers with Okuninushi, and is now considered a Kunitsukami. After building Japan with Okuninushi, he is said to have returned to Tokoyo no Kuni, the land of eternity.

dvl.name: Mithras
dvl.desc:
A sun god worshipped in Rome from the 1st to 4th century CE. A festival was held in his honor every winter solstice, a symbol of his alleged rebirth after death. 
Though hailed as a heroic god who delivers people from strife, his followers performed secret rites where they bathed in sacrificial animal blood.

dvl.name: Amon
dvl.desc:
One of the 72 demons of King Solomon's Ars Goetia and a Grand Marquis of Hell commanding 40 legions.
Grants his summoner knowledge of past and future. At times he brings about conflict, and at times mends it.
When Satan rebelled against God, Amon is said to have devotedly led a volunteer army to assist Satan.

dvl.name: Odin
dvl.desc:
A Great warrior and magician, seeker of wisdom and the chief of the Norse gods. He willingly sacrificed an eye to drink from the Well of Wisdom. As the chief of the gods, Odin will gladly welcome anyone with a warrior spirit.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Melchizedek
dvl.desc:
A Gnostic angel heralded as the savior of other angels, said to have been born of the goddess Sophia. He also appears in the Bible as Melchizedek, King of Justice.
In the book of Genesis, he is called both "priest of El Elyon" and "king of Salem."

dvl.name: Hachiman
dvl.desc:
The guardian god of the samurai who is also the most widely worshipped among Japan's various gods.
According to the history of his head shrine, Usa Shrine in Oita Prefecture, Emperor Ojin is Hachiman.
Some, however, believe Hachiman came from the influence of Taoism and Buddhism, muddying the truth of his identity.
Once the guardian of the Minamoto clan, he has been worshipped as the guardian god of samurai since the Kamakura period.

dvl.name: Hinokagutsuchi
dvl.desc:
The god of fire and a child of Izanagi and Izanami from Japanese mythology.
His flames caused the death of his mother, Izanami, for which an enraged Izanagi cut off his son's head.
According to the Kojiki, Hinokagutsuchi's corpse and spilled blood birthed many gods.

dvl.name: Okuninushi
dvl.desc:
A representative member of the Kunitsukami in Japanese mythology, Okuninushi presides over agriculture and medicine.
After overcoming difficult trials given to him by Susano-o, he founded the nation of Izumo with Susano-o's daughter Suseri-hime, making Okuninushi an ancestor of Izumo Takeru.
The Kojiki records him as fathering Take-Minakata and a total of 181 divine children with various goddesses.

dvl.name: Zeus
dvl.desc:
Chief god in Greek myth. Rules the 12 gods of Olympus as the omniscient, omnipotent god of the sky.
Though part of a polytheistic religion, Zeus bears absolute might rivaling that of a monotheistic god. He wields lightning strong enough to rend space itself.
After saving his siblings from their father (Cronus, who feared his children would usurp his throne), Zeus battled across and ultimately won control over the universe.

dvl.name: Demeter
dvl.desc:
A Greek goddess whose name means "Mother Earth." She is Zeus's elder sister and has a long history of worship.
Though known as a gentle goddess of fertility who taught humans to cultivate grain, she brings famine if angered. Of her, even Zeus is wary.
Because her knowledge helped birth civilization, and civilization requires law, she is also known as the bringer of law.

dvl.name: Gozu-Tennoh
dvl.desc: A Japanese Shinto-Buddhist syncretism and guardian deity of Gion Shoja. He is also called Muto Tenjin. In ancient China, he was said to be the son of Xi Wangmu and had a castle in northern Tenjiku with 80,000 subordinate deities. In Onmyodo, he is considered to be the god Tendo-Jin. Though many theories about his true identity exist, the Gion Gozu-Tennoh Goengi claims he is Yakushi Nyorai (Buddha) of the Pure Land. Many worship him to ward off pestilence.

dvl.name: Botis
dvl.desc:
One of the 72 demons of King Solomon's Ars Goetia. He is a Great President and Earl that leads 60 legions. It is said that he appears in the form of a fearsome viper and has knowledge of the past, present, and future. He will answer any question he is asked. 
He can also take a human form with large teeth, two horns, and a sword. All who see him are stricken with fear.

dvl.name: Guedhe
dvl.desc:
A Voodoo god of death, also known as Baron Samedi and Baron La Croix, who appears wearing a black tailcoat and top hat.
In Voodoo mythology, the souls of the dead must travel to Guinee, the land of the gods. Guedhe waits at the Eternal Crossroads, watching over these souls. He is extremely clever and knows of every human to have ever live. While also being a jovial deity fond of cigars and liquor.

dvl.name: Rahab
dvl.desc:
A monster of the sea appearing in the Old Testament. His name means "arrogant" and "violent."
He is known as a symbol of chaos, existing even before our world's creation. However, he was split in two for defying God, with half of him becoming the sky and the other half the sea. He now dwells in the Red Sea, and is known as the sea's primordial ruler.
He is often depicted as an enemy of Jewish people, and sometimes as the guardian angel of Egypt.
He is also found in Babylonian mythology, where he is the first monster born from the Abzu and Tiamat.

dvl.name: Kalki
dvl.desc:
One of the avatars of the Hindu god Vishnu.
His name has the meanings "eternity," "time," and "the one who destroys filth." He is often depicted as a hero riding a white steed. He is the last of Vishnu's ten avatars, a savior who appears in Kali Yuga, the age of darkness, to smite all evil and usher in the golden age of Krita Yuga.

dvl.name: Longinus
dvl.desc:
When Jesus was crucified at Golgotha, Longinus pierced his side with a lance to confirm his death.
Though a Roman Centurion, he was said to be blind. But when the blood of Jesus fell upon him, Longinus was healed. He converted to Christianity afterward, and he was eventually canonized as a saint. Because his lance was touched by the blood of Jesus, it is considered a holy relic.

dvl.name: Tiamat
dvl.desc:
The primordial goddess of Babylonian lore whose form resembles a dragon. She governs the sea and gave birth to many deities with her consort Apsu, the god of fresh water. When war broke out between her and the gods, she spawned 11 monsters to fight by her side, but they were defeated by the leader of the gods, Marduk. Her body was first ripped apart and then used to create the world.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Kangiten
dvl.desc: A version of Ganesha, the son of Shiva in Indian mythology, that has been adopted into Buddhism. Bestows many benefits, such as protection from misfortune, harmony between couples, and aid in conception. Often depicted as an embracing man and woman with elephant heads. Originally a violent god requiring strict adherence from its followers.

dvl.name: Hagen
dvl.desc:
A warrior appearing in the German epic poem "The Song of the Nibelungs" who served as King Gunther's loyal chief vassal.
Hagen assassinated the invulnerable Siegfried by stabbing him in the back, his one weak point, with a spear while Siegfried was drinking from a spring.
Afterward, following a hard-fought battle, Siegfried and King Gunther were captured. They were then beheaded by Kriemhild, Siegfried's wife.

dvl.name: Indra
dvl.desc:
A god of thunder from Indian mythology, who is known as Taishakuten in Buddhism.
In the oldest Indian holy scripture, the Rig Veda, he is a Deva, and is said to have fought numerous enemies, including Vritra, Asura, and Rakshasa.
He was adopted into Hinduism as a heroic god symbolizing thunder. After ceding his position as supreme god to Shiva and Vishnu, he became one of the Lokapala as the guardian of the East.

dvl.name: Moloch
dvl.desc:
An ancient Middle Eastern god worshipped in Canaan.
He is also known as "The Ruler of the Land of Tears," and "The Horrid King Besmeared with Children's Blood and Parents' Tears." A bronze statue of a man with a bull's head was placed at his altars.
In the Bible, he is known as a savage pagan god.

dvl.name: Unit 01: Dx2 Type
dvl.desc: An entity modeled after Evangelion Unit 01, which manifested as a result of Shinji Ikari's intense emotions. The influence of the Aura Gate has changed its appearance somewhat, but is as powerful a weapon against Angels as the original.

dvl.name: The 6th Angel
dvl.desc:
An entity strikingly similar to the Angel that attacked New Tokyo-Ⅲ. It is a fake created by Jabo Kakuryu in order to rattle Shinji Ikari's heart.
Though normally appearing as a kind of crystalline octahedron, it will change shape and attack based on the situation. The original 6th Angel fought with the Evas and was destroyed by a positron cannon.

dvl.name: The 10th Angel
dvl.desc:
An entity strikingly similar to the Angel that attacked New Tokyo-Ⅲ. It is a fake created by Jabo Kakuryu in order to rattle Shinji Ikari's heart.
It can deploy numerous A.T. Fields to create a solid defense, launch powerful attacks using rays of light, and can even consume its opponents and steal their abilities.
The original 10th Angel was a difficult foe, described as "the most powerful refusal type."

dvl.name: Camael
dvl.desc: Known as the angel of battle in Jewish mythology, as well as the one who controls the Powers. He is also a commander who leads the angels of destruction, punishment, and death. His name means "one who sees God." In addition, he is said to be the guardian angel of Tuesday and the ruler of Mars. He has an aggressive temperament, and will ruthlessly attack any who stand opposed to God.

dvl.name: Cait Sith
dvl.desc:
Cat spirits from the Scottish highlands whose kingdoms can be found in hollowed trees or abandoned houses. They possess green, intelligent eyes, and are said to understand human speech.
Cait means "cat" and Sith means "spirit," so Cait Sith are often depicted as black cats.

dvl.name: Dagon
dvl.desc:
A god from Ugaritic mythology, who by some accounts is said to be the father of Baal.
His name derives from the word for grain, and he was thought to bring bountiful harvests to the land.
Dagon was put in Cthulhu Mythos as a giant fish person. He is depicted holding a stone pillar while wailing.

dvl.name: Vivian
dvl.desc: A water fairy from Arthurian lore who takes the form of a beautiful woman, and is known as the Lady of the Lake. She is the guardian spirit of Lancelot, a knight of the Round Table, and lives together with several knights and servants in her palace under the illusionary lake. When King Arthur's sword broke in his battle against King Pellinore, Vivian granted him the holy sword Excalibur.

dvl.name: Lugh
dvl.desc:
The god of light from Celtic Mythology. Also called Lu or Lug, his name means "light" or "the radiant one."
He is said to be skilled in all arts, and is known as Long Arm for wielding the Brionac spear in battle.
Though said to have given birth to Cu Chulainn with Deichtine, daughter of Balor, Lugh's true wife is the earth goddess Bui. It is also said that Balor, despite being Lugh's greatest enemy, was his grandfather. Balor was defeated by Lugh at the Battle of Moytura, his wicked eye pierced.

dvl.name: Poltergeist
dvl.desc:
A mischievous type of ghost that appears inside of houses. Their name means "noisy ghost" in German.
Though they may play relatively harmless pranks such as making noise, they are also known to start fires and assault people.
Poltergeists only appear in houses with kids undergoing puberty. Some theories say that the children's unstable mental states are what causes them to appear.

dvl.name: Pendragon
dvl.desc:
The king of dragons in Arthurian lore. His name means ""head of the dragons"" and ""greatest dragon.""
When Arthur's father Uther was fighting against the Saxons, two comets like blazing infernos flew through the sky. Uther marked the occasion by henceforth referring to himself as Uther Pendragon. Arthur inherited the Pendragon name from him.
Pendragon would come to be associated with the king's authority. His figure can be seen, for example, in the emblem on the shields of British knights.

dvl.name: Apsu
dvl.desc: A god from Mesopotamian mythology known as the water-filled abyss. Apsu has existed since the birth of time. His fresh water, which covered and supported the land, combined with Tiamat and her primordial saltwater sea, to birth many gods. He is said to be the source of knowledge and wisdom, as well as a bringer of happiness and fertility.

dvl.name: Morrighan
dvl.desc:
A goddess appearing in Celtic mythology. One of the three goddesses of war. Her name means "Great Queen." She is said to be a deification of sovereignty and control that presides over destruction and victory.
In Celtic mythology she professed her love to Cu Chulainn, but was rejected. In anger, Morrighan transformed into various animals to obstruct his battle, but to no avail. She would later appear as an old woman and have Cu Chulainn heal her wounds. Afterwards, she offered him her aid.

dvl.name: Kali
dvl.desc:
A goddess of Indian mythology. She is one of the consorts of Shiva, the god of destruction.
The name "Kali" means "black one" and is derived from the word "kala" (black), but has also come to mean "goddess of time."
She is usually depicted with four arms, each of which is always carrying a blood-stained weapon or a severed head.
Kali is identified with Durga, an alternate aspect of Parvati transformed by anger at Asura into a fearsome form.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Lost Name
dvl.desc:
A dog-like demon the Liberators encountered in the Aura Gate. He is said to have been born from a certain legend, and appears unused to our world.
Though he was being used as a watchdog by another demon, he was able to break free with the Liberators' help. He is a trusty partner that will resolutely face down any foe. The Liberators started calling him ""Lost Name"" as he didn't have a name of his own.

dvl.name: Sukuna-Hikona
dvl.desc:
One of the gods of Japanese lore, who is also known as Sukuna-Hikona-no-Mikoto. Older tales speak of him as the son of Kamimusubi, but is the son of Takamimusubi according to the Nihonshoki. He was apparently so small that he fell through his parents' fingers at birth. Though he would normally be counted among the Amatsukami, he became blood-brothers with Okuninushi, and is now considered a Kunitsukami. After building Japan with Okuninushi, he is said to have returned to Tokoyo no Kuni, the land of eternity.
A freak accident at the Summoning Portal caused these demons with a different appearance to appear.

dvl.name: Loup-Garou
dvl.desc:
A type of werewolf originating in France. Though they appear human during the day, they take on their beastly form at night and attack humans.
Loup-Garou were once human, but were made into werewolves by a curse. It is said that there is no way to turn someone who has become one back to normal.

dvl.name: Queen Mab
dvl.desc:
A fairy queen from Celtic mythology whose name means "intoxication."
Though originally spoken of as something similar to a succubus, it is said that she became better known as a queen due to often being identified with Titania.
Queen Mab rules over Connacht, where she has many husbands. It is said that, in order to assign authority to people, she would give them mead mixed with her own blood.

dvl.name: Yggdrasil
dvl.desc:
A giant ash tree from Norse mythology which is also referred to as the World Tree and the Cosmic Tree. 
Its branches spread through the nine worlds and its trunk reaches high into the heavens, where it supports Alfheim, abode of the Light Elves.
Its three roots stretch into Jotunheim (home of the giants), Niflheim (the land of the dead), and the heavenly realm Asgard. It is said that Yggdrasil will survive Ragnarok, the twilight of the gods.

dvl.name: Narcissus
dvl.desc:
A flower god appearing in Greek mythology.
Though originally a profoundly beautiful young man, a curse making him unable to love anyone but his own reflection in the water was inflicted on him as a punishment for spurning the nymph Echo.
Narcissus, entranced by his own reflection in the water and unable to look away, eventually faded away and became the flower that now bears his name.
Narcissus's legend also serves as the etymology of the word narcissism.

dvl.name: Ainz
dvl.desc:
The leader of the guild Ainz Ooal Gown, and the ruler of the Great Tomb of Nazarick.
Though originally just an average office drone, when YGGDRASIL, a DMMO-RPG he was hooked on, was set to shut down, he wound up transported to another world in the form of his undead game avatar, which is known as an OVERLORD. Due to a misunderstanding on the part of his beloved subordinates, he is currently working towards conquering that other world.
Though he retains a human-like disposition for extreme caution when implementing plans, as an undead, he can also be quite cold-blooded.

dvl.name: Albedo
dvl.desc:
An otherworldly beauty serving as the leader of the Guardians of the Great Tomb of Nazarick. She is the self-proclaimed first wife of Ainz, and often quarrels with Shalltear over that position.
Albedo supports Ainz on multiple fronts with her impressive administrative and managerial prowess. Though undeniably a capable aide to him, her extreme love for Ainz often causes her to go overboard.

dvl.name: Shalltear
dvl.desc:
The guardian of the first, second and third floors of the Great Tomb of Nazarick. Though a charming girl with a unique manner of speech, her real form is that of a merciless true vampire.
Though she possesses the highest combat ability of the floor guardians, being bathed in too much blood will activate her skill, Blood Frenzy, causing her to lose herself in her urge for slaughter.
Though she has unusual tastes and preferences, Shalltear loves Ainz from the bottom of her heart. She frequently quarrels with Albedo over who will be his first wife.

dvl.name: Idun
dvl.desc:
A goddess in Norse Mythology. She is the wife of Bragi, the god of poetry, as well as the keeper of the golden apples.
She has eyes like a clear blue sky and a gentle demeanor. Idun is considered among the most beautiful in Asgard, alongside Freya. The golden apples she keeps are said to be how the gods maintain their eternal youth.

dvl.name: Mephisto
dvl.desc:
More accurately, Mephistopheles. He is an archduke of hell whose name means "not loving light."
He is widely known as the demon summoned by Georg Faust, and is considered the most fearsome commander of Hell after Satan. However, he despises having fallen into Hell, and resents humans for being granted the chance for salvation.
In addition to his vast knowledge in the fields of astronomy and astrology, he is very proficient in illusion, which he can use to manipulate all five senses.

dvl.name: Masakado
dvl.desc:
A demon whose form is based on hero of the Kanto provinces who lived in the Middle Heian Period, Taira no Masakado.
Taira no Masakado believed in Myōken Bosatsu, and was served by seven shadow warriors who were likened to the stars of the Big Dipper. Even after he started being worshipped as a guardian deity of Tokyo, he would choose humans with a strong desire to protect Tokyo to take under his command as shadow warriors.
Reborn as a mighty demon through the power of Taira no Masakado, he has long protected and supported Tokyo from the shadows.

dvl.name: Barbatos
dvl.desc:
One of the 72 Demons appearing in King Solomon's Ars Goetia.
Though both an Earl and Duke of Hell, is it said that he was a Virtue before falling.
He has many powers, including the power to find treasures hidden away by magicians, as well as the the power to understand the voices of birds, dogs, and all other animals.
He is also said to be able to see into the past and future, and even has the power to help friends settle disputes.

dvl.name: Kuzuryu
dvl.desc:
Kuzuryu, whose name translates to 'nine-headed dragon,' is a revered dragon deity featured in numerous legends across Japan.
Also known as Kuzuryu Daijin and Kuzuryu Kongen, he is particularly celebrated in the Togakushi area as a spirit that rules over rain and water.
Kuzuryu's temperament changes depending on the legend. In one instance, during the Nara period (710-794 CE) in Heijo-Kyo, he was regarded as a good deity who ate the Oni causing a plague. In another, however, he attacked villagers on Mt. Kano and had to be slain by Yamato Takeru.
Within Buddhism, Kuzuryu is esteemed as Washu-Kitsu Ryuu Ou, one of the Eight Great Naga Kings.

dvl.name: Metatron
dvl.desc: An existence birthed from Vanitas's malice, this powerful new entity is based on Metatron. Metatron, who is referred to by over 70 different names, is said to be either the highest-ranking angel or, according to some, to be God himself. The name 'Metatron' is derived from a word meaning 'he who serves the throne.' In Judaism, Metatron is considered the most important angel. He provided guidance to Moses during his attempt to lead the Jews out of Egypt and parted the sea when Moses and his followers were being pursued by Egypt's forces.

dvl.name: Old Ones
dvl.desc:
Lifeforms appearing in the Cthulhu Mythos that, long ago, visited Earth from the reaches of outer space. They are also known as Elder Things.
These beings are fundamentally different from Earth's lifeforms, lacking sex or genders and reproducing through spores instead.
Their civilization once spanned the entire planet, with sprawling cities built across its surface. However, their dominance waned due to wars with other species and a severe cold wave. It is believed that the majority of the survivors are now in a state of artificial hibernation.

dvl.name: Ame no Futotama
dvl.desc:
The Japanese god of divination and religious rituals, who appears in the Kojiki and Nihon Shoki. He is said to be the divine ancestor of the Inbe clan, which served the Imperial Family.
When Amaterasu was hiding in Amano-Iwato and the world was covered in darkness, he performed the Futomani, a divination using the shoulder bones of a male deer from Mt. Amanokagu.

dvl.name: Osiris
dvl.desc:
An underworld deity appearing in Egyptian mythology. He is the chief god of death and eldest brother of the four pillar gods born between Geb and Nut. He is also the father of Horus, as well as the brother and husband of Isis.
He was once known as a god of vegetation and agriculture, and succeeded the sun god Ra, becoming the final god to rule over the land. However, he was betrayed and murdered by his younger brother Seth. After being revived by Isis, he became king of the underworld.
His believers thought that Osiris's just rule would bring eternal splendor in the afterlife and therefore worshipped him as a righteous god.

dvl.name: Cleopatra
dvl.desc:
More specifically, "Cleopatra VII." She was the last Queen of Ptolemaic Egypt, whose name in Greek means "glory of the father."
She is known for her unparalleled beauty, and charmed many a man with her lovely singing voice and conversational skills.
So potent were her charms that many say, "had her nose been just a bit shorter, it would have changed the course of history."

dvl.name: Queen Frost
dvl.desc:
The queen of Jack Frosts. In a certain castle, she lives and rules over countless Jack Frosts.
Though she wields ice magic, she is not fond of combat. Instead, she values peace and love. Queen Frost's appearance, abounding with dignity and grace, matches her royal status.

dvl.name: Femto
dvl.desc:
The form taken by Griffith, leader of the Band of the Hawk, after being transfigured through the use of the Crimson Behelit into a member of the God Hand.
Though he normally existed in the Astral World and could only manifest during The Invocation of Doom, through certain means he was incarnated into Mortal World.

dvl.name: Kumbhanda
dvl.desc:
A demon from Hindu mythology and a female monster that drains energy from humans.
